on|publisher=|access-date=2017-02-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224053659/http://myxtv.com/shows/brave-combat-federation|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action|S+A]]\n* [[ESPN 5]]\n* [[MTV India]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/media/entertainment/mtv-mercury-sports-sign-multi-year-deal-to-bring-brave-fights-reality-show-on-tv/articleshow/67157002.cms|title=MTV, Mercury Sports sign multi-year deal to bring Brave fights, reality show on TV|accessdate=December 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* Fite TV<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fite.tv/vl/p/brave-combat-federation/|title=Brave Combat Federation Streams & Videos|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===BRAVE TV===\n\nBrave Combat Federation announced last year the creation of BRAVE TV, an online subscription service in which fans would be able to watch live events, as well as reruns of old shows. Brave 23 was available on the newly-formed online streaming platform to fans from all over the world, except for those territories contemplated with preexisting TV deals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bravefights.com/brave-combat-federation-to-live-stream-historical-jordan-event-for-free/|title=BRAVE COMBAT FEDERATION TO LIVE STREAM HISTORICAL JORDAN EVENT FOR FREE|publisher=BRAVE Fights}}</ref>\n\n===Talents===\n* [[Cyrus Fees]]: Play-by-play commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravefights.com/cyrus-fees-is-confirmed-as-brave-1-official-announcer/|title=Cyrus Fees is confirmed as Brave 1 official announcer - BRAVE Fights|website=www.bravefights.com}}</ref>\n* [[Frankie Edgar]]: Color Commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/mma/mma-news-frankie-edgar-to-be-color-commentator-for-brave-3|title=MMA News: Frankie Edgar to commentate at Brave 3|date=22 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Nate Quarry]]: Color Commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wn.com/brave_6_kazakhstan_breakdown_with_nate_rock_quarry|title=Brave 6 Kazakhstan Breakdown With Nate Rock Quarry|website=World News}}</ref>\n* Alex Soto: Color Commentator\n* Phil Campbell: Color Commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmauk.net/2018/09/13/brave-combat-federation-signs-tv-talent-from-belfast/|title=Brave Combat Federation signs TV talent from Belfast|publisher=MMA UK}}</ref>\n* Carlos Kremer: Cage announcer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravefights.com/brave-confirms-carlos-kremer-as-cage-announcer/|title=Brave confirms Carlos Kremer as cage announcer - BRAVE Fights|website=www.bravefights.com}}</ref>\n* [[Cristiane Justino|Cris Cyborg]]: Guest commentator\n* Noel O'Keefe<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmacharge.com/noel-okeeffe-to-join-brave-commentary-team-in-abu-dhabi/|title=Noel O\u2019Keeffe to join Brave commentary team in Abu Dhabi|publisher=MMA Charge}}</ref>\n* Kirik Jenness<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdnonline.com/Details/320154/MMA-expert-Jenness-joins-Brave-commentary-panel|title=MMA expert Jenness joins Brave commentary panel|publisher=Gulf Daily News}}</ref>\n\n==Film Production==\n===SMILE - Documentary===\n[[File:Poster_of_SMILE.jpg|thumb|right|Poster of SMILE]]\nBrave Combat Federation has announced initiation of operations of their subsidiary film production unit named Brave Films. To commence operations the film production unit produced the television documentary-drama \"SMILE\"<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7074622/</ref> on 26 June during Eid.<ref>http://www.gdnonline.com/Details/220315/Brave-launch-SMILE-trailer</ref> The documentary narrates the story of the featherweight champion of Brave Combat Federation and behind the scenes of his training leading to the championship bout. The content was shot extensively in [[Montpellier]], France and Tijuana, Mexico apart from locations in Bahrain and in [[Abu Dhabi]], United Arab Emirates. The initiative was publicised to popularise mixed martial arts and to showcase the lifestyle of fighters<ref>http://thefangarage.com/articles/11097-brave-launches-trailer-for-documentary-based-on-the-life-of-elias-boudegezdane</ref> and marks the launch of \u201cBrave Films\u201d, a film production segment by Brave Combat Federation.<ref>http://www.arabsmma.com/trailer-mma-film-smile-boudegzdame/</ref>\n\n==BRAVE International Combat Week==\nIn February 2017, KHK MMA and [[IMMAF]] announced, during a press conference, a partnership which would see the Amateur World Championships move from [[Las Vegas]] to [[Bahrain]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://immaf.org/event/2017-immaf-world-championships/|title=2017 IMMAF World Championships|publisher=IMMAF}}</ref>\n\n[[IMMAF]] president [[Kerrith Brown]] was present at the official announcement, in which Bahrain MMA Association president Khalid Abdulaziz Al Khayyat praised Sheikh [[Khalid bin Hamad Al Khalifa]]'s commitment to creating a culture for mixed martial arts in the region and claimed this shift as a deal closer for the world championships to move to Bahrain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/mma/mma-news-bahrain-to-host-2017-immaf-world-championships-of-amateur-mma|title=MMA News: Bahrain to host 2017 IMMAF World Championships of Amateur MMA|publisher=Sports Keeda}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the world championships, BRAVE president [[Mohammed \"The Hawk\" Shahid]] announced in the same press conference that the promotion would host a show in the same week as the World Championships, saying it would be \"one of the biggest fight weeks we've seen in Middle East combat sports history\", which was named International Combat Week<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=67&v=ECgGumM4-Nk|title=KHK MMA CEO confirms IMMAF World Championship during International Combat Week|publisher=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOrganized under the patronage of His Highness Sheikh [[Nasser bin Hamad Al Khalifa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizbahrain.com/brave-international-combat-week-starts/|title=BRAVE International Combat Week starts|publisher=Biz Bahrain}}</ref> the first International Combat Week was held from November 12 to November 19, with BRAVE 9 taking place on November 17, featuring two title fights.\n\n===2018===\nIn March 2018, [[IMMAF]] president [[Kerrith Brown]] officially announced the return of the Amateur World Championships to Bahrain for 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://immaf.org/2018-2019-immaf-world-championships-announced-for-bahrain-2/|title=2018 & 2019 IMMAF WORLD CHAMPIONSHIPS ANNOUNCED FOR BAHRAIN|publisher=IMMAF}}</ref>\n\nThe 2018 International Combat Week took place between November 11 and November 18, with BRAVE 18 taking place on November 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bna.bh/en/BRAVEInternationalCombatWeekwillcementBahrainsinternationalposition.aspx?cms=q8FmFJgiscL2fwIzON1%2BDgJ1toQfYlLVqhxjrhg9TpA%3D|title=BRAVE International Combat Week will cement Bahrain's international position|publisher=Bahrain News Agency}}</ref>\n\nBRAVE 18 crowned a new Lightweight champion in Abdul-Kareem Al-Selwady, and Stephen Loman retained his Bantamweight title by defending it against Brazil's Felipe Efrain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-18-results-al-selwady-destroys-x-ufc-fighter-to-become-brave-world-champion/|title=Brave 18 Results: Al-Selwady destroys X-UFC fighter to become Brave world champion|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of current Brave CF fighters]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MMA organizations}}\n\n[[Category:Mixed martial arts organizations]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial arts television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advert|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|MMA promoter based in Bahrain}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name             = BRAVE Combat Federation\n|logo             = Brave CF logo.jpg\n|logo_size        = 300px\n|type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n|founder          = [[Khalid bin Hamad Al Khalifa]]\n|key_people       = [[Mohammed \"The Hawk\" Shahid]] (President), [[Valeria Lang]] (COO)\n|industry         = [[Mixed martial arts]] [[promoter (entertainment)|promotion]]|\n|parent           = \n|homepage         = {{url|www.bravecf.com}}\n|foundation       = {{start date and age|df=yes|2016||}}\n|location_city    = [[Seef]]\n|location_country = [[Bahrain]]\n}}\n'''BRAVE Combat Federation''' is the largest<ref>{{cite web|url=https://powcastsports.com/stephenlomanin-manila-for-brave/|title=FILIPINO STARS AT THE CORE OF BRAVE\u2019S GLOBAL EXPANSION - Powcast Sports|publisher=}}</ref> [[mixed martial arts]] (MMA) [[promoter (entertainment)|promotion]] in the Middle East. The organization was established on 23 September 2016 by Sheikh [[Khalid bin Hamad Al Khalifa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulf-insider.com/brave-new-world-interview/|title=A Brave New World - Interview - Gulf Insider - The Arabian Review|publisher=}}</ref> BRAVE Combat Federation features mixed martial artists from more than 40 nations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manilastandard.net/spotlight/285918/BRAVE-combat-federation-takes-global-mma-vision-to-the-philippines.html/|title=BRAVE Combat Federation takes global MMA vision to the Philippines - Manila Standard|publisher=}}</ref> located in five continents. BRAVE Combat Federation events are aired though multiple media partners including [[El Rey Network]], [[Globosat|Combate]], [[Myx TV]], [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action|S+A]] [[ESPN 5]] and [[Bahrain Radio and Television Corporation]]. BRAVE Combat Federation produced six pay-per-view events apart from announcing events in [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.superlutas.com.br/noticias/57669/com-ex-ufc-no-card-BRAVE-3-anuncia-venda-de-ingressos-para-evento-no-brasil/|title=Com ex-UFC no card, BRAVE 3 anuncia venda de ingressos para evento no Brasil|date=22 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://esportes.yahoo.com/noticias/BRAVE-3-bananada-tira-sarro-110040480.html|title=BRAVE 3: Bananada tira sarro de grito caracter\u00edstico de ex-UFC e companheiros|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe organization was formally launched in 2016 and has established operations in [[Dublin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fightstoremedia.ie/brave-combat-federation-coming-ireland/|title=Brave Combat Federation coming to Ireland - Fightstore Media|date=12 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref> [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] and [[Mumbai]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport360.com/article/other/202676/bahrains-brave-combat-federation-initiates-mma-expansion-to-india/|title=Bahrain\u2019s Brave Combat Federation initiates MMA expansion to India|publisher=}}</ref> prior to launching events and for talent relations. Brave Combat Federation, alongside the holding company, KHK MMA and Bahrain Mixed Martial Arts Federation hosted the [[IMMAF]] World Championships in November, 2017.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsofbahrain.com/viewNews.php?ppId=30085&pid=21&MNU=|title=Bahrain to host IMMAF World Championships|publisher=}}</ref> a partnership which was renewed for 2018 and 2019<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mma-mena.com/Newsdet.aspx?id=326|title=Bahrain to host 2018 and 2019 IMMAF World Championships|publisher=MMA Mena}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===KHK MMA===\nKHK MMA is a [[Bahrain]] based mixed martial arts organization which promotes the growth of mixed martial arts in the region. KHK MMA is also the holding company of Brave Combat Federation. KHK MMA was established by Sheikh Khalid bin Hamad Al Khalifa.<ref>http://www.bna.bh/portal/en/news/737614</ref> Bahrain MMA is the official gym for KHK MMA.<ref>http://www.timeoutbahrain.com/sportandoutdoor/features/74651-mixed-martial-arts-in-bahrain</ref> KHK MMA launched operations of Brave Combat federation on July 27, 2016 and officially launched the promotion on 23 September 2016.<ref>http://www.bna.bh/portal/en/news/737614</ref> KHK MMA Fight Team features fighters from multiple promotions including [[Khabib Nurmagomedov]], [[Frankie Edgar]], [[Jose Torres (mixed martial arts)|Jose Torres]] <ref>http://www.arabsmma.com/28680-2/</ref> and [[James Gallagher (mixed martial arts)|James Gallagher]].<ref>http://www.bna.bh/portal/en/news/737140</ref> Coaches and UFC Hall of Famers like [[Renzo Gracie]], [[John Kavanagh (martial artist)|John Kavanagh]], Bob Schirmer, and Pete Williams are also working with KHK MMA.<ref>http://mmajunkie.com/2015/08/fighters-and-trainers-discuss-khk-chances-to-become-best-mma-camp-in-the-world</ref>\n\n===Launch of Brave Combat Federation===\n\nAfter establishing KHK MMA as a rising force within the MMA world,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2016/1/8/10735882/khk-mma-founder-bahrain-prince-khaled-hamad-alkhalifa-frankie-edgar-khabib-mma-middle-east|title=Bringing MMA to the Middle East: An interview with KHK MMA founder Mohammed Shahid|publisher=Bloody Elbow}}</ref> Sheikh Khalid bin Hamad Al Khalifa started working towards introducing a global event.\n\nBRAVE Combat Federation was officially launched during a press conference held in the Kingdom of Bahrain on July 27, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-promotion-launched-mohammad-fakhreddine-headline/|title=\"Brave\" Promotion Launched, Mohammad Fakhreddine to Headline!|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref> Less than two months later, [[Brave 1: The Beginning]] took place in Isa Town, Bahrain, on September 23, 2016, a date which coincided with Sheikh Khalid's birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-1-fakhreddine-vs-vieira-fight-card/|title=Brave 1 \"The Beginning\" Fight Card + Results|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref> Brave rounded up the first few months of its operations with [[Brave 2: Dynasty]], also taking place in [[Bahrain]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-2-results-boudegzdame-submits-watson-style/|title=Brave 2 Results: Elias Boudegzdame Submits Watson With Style|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n\n======Brazil======\nAfter capturing the attention of the MENA region, with two shows in Bahrain, Brave took the step to further develop the brand in other regions, as well as strengthening Bahraini sports' position in the international scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-3-announced-in-brazil/|title=Mohammed Shahid Announces Brave 3 In Brazil|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref> Brazil was chosen to be the first country to host a Brave event outside its homeland, with future Lightweight champions Lucas \"Mineiro\" Martins and Luan Santiago, as well as former Welterweight titleholder Carlston Harris among the fighters who made their promotional debuts at [[Brave 3: Battle In Brazil|Brave 3: Battle in Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-3-brazil-success-results/|title=Brave 3 Brazil A Success. Check Out The Results.|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref> The fight card was also the first appearance of former UFC champion and KHK MMA fighter [[Frankie Edgar]] as a color commentator<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bravefights.com/mma-legend-frankie-edgar-brave-3/)|title=MMA LEGEND FRANKIE EDGAR TO BE COLOR COMMENTATOR FOR BRAVE 3|publisher=Brave Fights}}</ref>\n\n======First World champion======\nContinuing its trend of international fight nights, Brave Combat Federation made its debut in Abu Dhabi and crowned its first-ever world champion. French-Algerian submission specialist Elias Boudegzdame defeated Masio Fullen in the main event of [[Brave 4: Unstoppable]] and became the promotion's maiden Featherweight world champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thefangarage.com/articles/10164-brave-4-results--boudegzdame-crowned-champion-atif-suffers-defeat|title=Brave 4 Results \u2013 Boudegzdame crowned Champion, Atif suffers defeat|publisher=The Fan Garage}}</ref>\n\nThe show also witnessed the promotional debut of Middle East superstar Mohammad Fakhreddine, who was scheduled to headline [[Brave 1: The Beginning]] before he suffered an injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bahrainthisweek.com/fakhreddine-injured-out-of-brave-main-event/|title=Fakhreddine Injured, Out Of BRAVE Main Event\n|publisher=Bahrain This Week}}</ref> \"The Latest\" faced off against Brazil's Vinicius Cruz and won by TKO in the second round.\n\n======Trips to India, Kazakhstan, and Mexico======\nAfter Brazil and the United Arab Emirates, Brave continued to travel around the world, as [[India]], [[Kazakhstan]], and [[Mexico]] were all treated to events between April and July.\n\n[[Brave 5: Go For Glory]] took place in [[Mumbai]], [[India]], on April 22, and had an anti-climactic main event, as Carl Booth and Tahar Hadbi fought to a No Contest, due to a timekeeping error.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sherdog.com/events/Brave-Combat-Federation-Brave-5-Go-for-Glory-59367|title=Brave Combat Federation Brave 5: Go for Glory|publisher=Sherdog}}</ref>\n\n[[Brave 6: Kazakhstan]] happened a week later, in [[Almaty]], where future Super Lightweight world champion Eldar Eldarov bested Brazilian Henrique Rasputin by TKO. It was also home to the first-ever Brave female fight, as Flyweight Mariya Agapova beat Yulia Litvinceva by TKO in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmasucka.com/2017/04/29/brave-6-eldarov-picks-second-win-festival-knockouts-submissions/|title=Brave 6: Eldarov picks up second win after festival of knockouts and submissions|publisher=MMA Sucka}}</ref>\n\nFinally, Brave 7 took place in [[Mexico]], and future world title challenger Alejandro \"Pato\" Martinez came out victorious in a grudge match against Fabian Quintanar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-7-results-pato-submits-quintanar-younger-fakhreddine-debuts-tko/|title=Brave 7 Results: Pato Submits Quintanar; Younger Fakhreddine Debuts with TKO|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref>\n\n======Two new World champions======\nFor Brave 8: The Rise of Champions, the promotion went back to [[Curitiba]], [[Brazil]], after its successful debut in March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmapremium.com.br/brave-combat-federation-retorna-ao-brasil-com-duas-disputas-de-titulo/|title=Brave Combat Federation retorna ao Brasil com duas disputas de t\u00edtulo|publisher=MMA Premium}}</ref> It was the first time Brave put two different titles on the line, with Welterweights Carl Booth and Mohammad Fakhreddine initially scheduled to face off, as well as Light Heavyweights Klidson de Abreu and Timo Feucht.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lance.com.br/lutas/com-duas-disputas-titulo-brave-anuncia-card-completo-para-curitiba.html|title=Com duas disputas de t\u00edtulo, Brave anuncia card completo para Curitiba|publisher=Lance}}</ref>\n\nOn the eve of weigh-ins, Fakhreddine was forced to pull out of the fight after feeling ill during the weight-cut process. He was substituted by Carlston Harris,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportv.globo.com/site/combate/noticia/2017/08/fakhreddine-passa-mal-e-harris-luta-pelo-titulo-dos-meio-medios-no-brave-8.html|title=Fakhreddine passa mal, e Harris luta pelo t\u00edtulo dos meio-m\u00e9dios no Brave 8|publisher=Combate}}</ref> who ended up surprising Booth and winning the title by decision.\n\nIn the main event, Klidson de Abreu bested Timo Feucht and became the first Brazilian champion for BRAVE <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.terra.com.br/esportes/lance/klidson-de-abreu-finaliza-e-ganha-cinturao-inedito-no-brave-8,0378c4b6330c04ac876a60138ec03d0c3s3vytab.html|title=Klidson de Abreu finaliza e ganha cintur\u00e3o in\u00e9dito no Brave 8\n|publisher=Terra}}</ref>\n\n======Return to Bahrain with International Combat Week======\nFor the year's last event, Brave decided to create the first-ever International Combat Week, in partnership with the [[IMMAF]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://immaf.org/immaf-heads-attend-latest-immaf-world-championships-brave-9-press-conference-in-bahrain-2/|title=IMMAF heads attend latest IMMAF World Championships & Brave 9 press conference in Bahrain|publisher=IMMAF.org}}</ref> The agreement stated that the ICW would happen for, at least, the next three years,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://immaf.org/2018-2019-immaf-world-championships-announced-for-bahrain-2/|title=2018 & 2019 IMMAF WORLD CHAMPIONSHIPS ANNOUNCED FOR BAHRAIN|publisher=IMMAF.org}}</ref> with a Brave show closing out the Amateur World Championships.\n\nBrave 9: The Kingdom of Champions also crowned two new titleholders, at Lightweight and Bantamweight.\n\nOttman Azaitar beat Alejandro \"Pato\" Mart\u00ednez in the main event to capture the Lightweight belt, while Stephen Loman knocked out Gurdarshan Mangat to become the first-ever Bantamweight champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaindia.com/brave-9-the-kingdom-of-champions-live-review-and-results/|title=BRAVE 9 \u2013 The Kingdom Of Champions: Live review and results|publisher=MMA India}}</ref>\n\nElias Boudegzdame was initially scheduled to defend his Featherweight title against Lucas \"Mineiro\" Martins, but the bout was called off after the challenger fell ill during the weight cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmabrasil.com.br/lucas-mineiro-passa-mal-e-esta-fora-do-brave-9|title=Lucas Mineiro passa mal e est\u00e1 fora do Brave 9|publisher=MMA Brasil}}</ref>\n\nMMA legend and Brave ambassador [[Wanderlei Silva]] attended the event, as well as [[Frankie Edgar]], who served as the color commentator for the broadcast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightbookmma.com/mma-icons-wanderlei-silva-and-frankie-edgar-witness-historical-brave-9-public-weigh-in/|title=MMA icons Wanderlei Silva and Frankie Edgar witness historical Brave 9 public weigh-in|publisher=Fightbook MMA}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n\n======First title defense======\n\nAfter not being able to defend his belt at Brave 9, Elias \"Smile\" Boudegzdame was scheduled to take on Jakub Kowalewicz in the main event of Brave 10,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://conandaily.com/2018/02/24/polands-jakub-kowalewicz-to-challenge-brave-cf-featherweight-champion-elias-boudegzdame/|title=Poland\u2019s Jakub Kowalewicz to challenge Brave CF Featherweight Champion Elias Boudegzdame|publisher=Conan Daily}}</ref> the first event of 2018, which also served as Brave's debut in [[Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/news/brave-announces-full-fight-card-for-jordan-debut|title=BRAVE announces full fight card for Jordan debut|publisher=Mixed Martial Arts}}</ref>\n\nBoudegzdame made history in the main event of Brave 10, as he successfully defended his Featherweight title with a fourth-round submission of Kowalewicz, in a night marked by a clean sweep of Jordanian fighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mymmanews.com/brave-10-results/|title=Brave 10 Results \u2013 Boudegzdame retains belt, Jordanian stars get the clean sweep|publisher=My MMA News}}</ref>\n\n======Return to Brazil and Indonesia debut======\n\nIn March 2018, the promotion returned for its third event in [[Brazil]], this time in [[Belo Horizonte]], for another title doubleheader.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-combat-federation-announces-brave-11-fight-card/|title=Brave Combat Federation announces Brave 11 fight card|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref> Lucas \"Mineiro\" Martins won the interim Lightweight belt in the main event, beating Luan \"Miau\" Santiago by TKO in the last seconds of their fight,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportv.globo.com/combate/videos/v/lucas-mineiro-vence-luan-miau-por-nocaute-pelo-cinturao-interino-dos-pesos-leve-brave-11/6661775/|title=Lucas Mineiro vence Luan Miau por nocaute pelo cintur\u00e3o interino dos pesos leve Brave 11|publisher=Sportv}}</ref> while Klidson de Abreu successfully defended his Light Heavyweight throne by submitting Matt Baker,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportv.globo.com/combate/videos/v/klidson-de-abreu-vence-matt-baker-por-finalizacao-pelo-peso-meio-pesado-no-brave-11/6661867/|title=Klidson de Abreu vence Matt Baker por finaliza\u00e7\u00e3o pelo peso-meio-pesado no Brave 11|publisher=Sportv}}</ref> who stood in for Kennedy Nzechukwu, forced to pull out due to injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fightgeek.asia/2018/03/29/champ-klidson-de-abreu-defend-title-matt-baker-brave-11/|title=CHAMP KLIDSON DE ABREU TO DEFEND TITLE AGAINST MATT BAKER AT BRAVE 11|publisher=Fight Geek Asia}}</ref>\n \nIn May, Brave continued to visit new destinations, this time traveling to [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]], for Brave 12: KHK Legacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/mma/brave-12-khk-legacy-fight-card-announced|title=Brave 12: KHK Legacy fight card announced|publisher=Sports Keeda}}</ref>\n\nIn the main event, Eldar Eldarov continued his winning streak by outpointing Brian Hooi in the scorecards, going 3-0 for Brave CF.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mma-today.com/brave-12-recap-prospects-khalid-taha-eldar-eldarov-shine-jakarta-ufc-vet-mafra-loses-knee-injury|title=BRAVE 12: PROSPECTS KHALID TAHA, ELDAR ELDAROV, MARAT MAGOMEDOV SHINE IN JAKARTA; UFC VET MAFRA LOSES BY KNEE INJURY|publisher=MMA Today}}</ref>\n\n======Europe Evolution======\nBrave's maiden trip to Europe took place at [[SSE Arena, Belfast|The SSE Arena]], in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], as the promotion organized BRAVE 13: Europe Evolution, on June 9, with 28 fighters from 15 nations in action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmauk.net/2018/05/22/full-fight-card-revealed-for-brave-13-europe-evolution-in-belfast/|title=Full Fight card revealed for Brave 13: Europe Evolution in Belfast|publisher=MMA UK}}</ref>\n\nIn the main event, Bantamweight champion Stephen Loman beat Frans Mlambo, a training partner of [[Conor McGregor]], in a rematch of their 2016 fight, back at Brave 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/6/9/17444540/brave-cf-13-results-stephen-loman-retains-bantamweight-title|title=Brave CF 13 results: Stephen Loman retains bantamweight title|publisher=MMA Fighting}}</ref>\n\nThe [[UFC]] superstar was in attendance to watch Mlambo and his teammate Cian Cowley, who had a successful debut, stopping Daniel Olejniczak to score his first professional MMA victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsjoe.ie/mma/conor-mcgregor-cian-cowley-dressing-room-163175|title=WATCH: Conor McGregor surprises Cian Cowley in his dressing room after victory|publisher=SportsJoe}}</ref>\n\n======African debut======\nBrave Combat Federation became the first global MMA promotion to do a show in [[Africa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://topsportsasia.com/2018/07/02/brave-cfs-brave-14-is-africas-first-international-mma-event/|title=Brave CF\u2019s \u2018Brave 14\u2019 is Africa\u2019s first international MMA event|publisher=Top Sports Asia}}</ref> as the organization hosted Brave 14, in [[Tangier]], [[Morocco]], on August 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmamotion.net/2018/07/24/report-fight-card-announced-for-brave-14-morocco/|title=Report: Fight card announced for Brave 14, Morocco|publisher=MMA Motion}}</ref>\n\nThe event was hosted under the patronage of [[King Mohammed VI]], the king of [[Morocco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdnonline.com/Details/383110/Brave-14-to-be-hosted-under-Morocco-King-patronage|title=Brave 14 to be hosted under Morocco King patronage|publisher=Gulf Daily News}}</ref>\n\nIn the main event, then-Lightweight champion Ottman Azaitar moved up to Welterweight to face Danijel Kokora and came out victorious via first-round TKO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/ottman-azaitar-jeremy-kennedy-victorious-brave-14/|title=Ottman Azaitar and Jeremy Kennedy victorious at Brave 14|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref>\n\nA few weeks after his appearance at Brave 14, Azaitar was stripped of his Lightweight title for not defending it. The vacated belt would be contested later in the year, at Brave 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mymmanews.com/ottman-azaitar-stripped//|title=Ottman Azaitar stripped of Brave Combat Federation championship belt|publisher=My MMA News}}</ref>\n\nThe show was also marked by the debuts of former [[UFC]] fighter [[Jeremy Kennedy]], who beat Danyel Pilo in the co-main event,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mma-today.com/brave-cf-14-jbc-is-back-ufc-alum-jeremy-kennedy-scores-1-of-7-big-kos-in-morocco|title=BRAVE CF 14 RESULTS/CLIPS: JBC IS BACK \u2013 UFC ALUM JEREMY KENNEDY SCORES 1 OF 7 BIG KOS IN MOROCCO|publisher=MMA Today}}</ref> and future Welterweight world champion Abdoul Abdouraguimov, winner via TKO in the first round against Sidney Wheeler.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://conandaily.com/2018/08/26/photos-abdoul-abdouraguimov-vs-sidney-wheeler-at-brave-14-morocco/|title=[PHOTOS] Abdoul Abdouraguimov vs Sidney Wheeler at \u2018Brave 14: Morocco\u2019|publisher=Conan Daily News}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, the Moroccan crowd witnessed Brave's fastest-ever KO, as Djamil Chan ended Alejandro \"Pato\" Martinez's night at 29 seconds of their bout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/fastest-ko-marks-brave-14s-preliminary-card/|title=Fastest KO marks Brave 14\u2019s preliminary card|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref>\n\n======New territories and return to Abu Dhabi======\nAfter its first trip to [[Africa]], Brave returned to [[South America]], this time hosting its first-ever [[Colombia]] event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmasucka.com/2018/08/27/brave-15-marks-promotions-debut-in-colombia/|title=BRAVE 15 marks promotion\u2019s debut in Colombia|publisher=MMA Sucka}}</ref> Brave 15 took place in [[Bucaramanga]] and featured former [[UFC]] standout [[Godofredo Pepey]] taking on local star Alex \"Rolo\" Torres in the main event, and other six Brazilian fighters scheduled to take on other Latin American athletes from [[Mexico]], [[Argentina]], [[Colombia]] and [[Peru]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mixedmartialarts.com/news/brave-15-fight-card-announced|title=Brave 15 fight card announced|publisher=Mixed Martial Arts}}</ref> with a clean sweep for [[Brazil]], including Pepey submitting Torres and debut victories for Featherweight Gabriel \"Fly\" Miranda and Welterweight Geraldo \"Luan Santana\" Neto<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmasucka.com/2018/09/08/brave-15-brazil-dominates-topped-by-godofredo-pepey-picking-up-first-round-submission/|title=Brave 15 Results \u2013 Brazil dominates in Colombia, topped by Godofredo Pepey\u2019s first-round finish over \"Rolo\"|publisher=Mixed MMA Sucka}}</ref>\n\nSandwiched between two events in new territories (the other being Brave 17, in [[Pakistan]]) was the return of Brave to [[Abu Dhabi]]. The fight card for Brave 16 was topped by a title doubleheader as Carlston Harris (Welterweight) and Elias Boudegzdame (Featherweight) looked to defend their crowns in the two main fights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmasucka.com/2018/08/31/brave-16-full-card-announced-two-title-fights-and-a-stellar-undercard/|title=Brave 16 full card announced, two title fights and a stellar undercard|publisher=MMA Sucka}}</ref>\n\nHowever, they were both bested by Jarrah Al-Selawe and [[Bubba Jenkins]], respectively, and two new champions were crowned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mma-today.com/brave-16-live-results-recaps-clips-from-harris-vs-al-silawi-and-all-the-action-from-abu-dhabi|title=BRAVE 16: JARRAH AL-SILAWE & BUBBA JENKINS TAKE HOME TITLES IN ABU DHABI|publisher=MMA Today}}</ref>\n\nAs in other countries, Brave also became the first global event to host a fight night in [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hamariweb.com/enews/amp/karim-to-lead-pakistan-s-first-ever-mma-event_nid2389862.aspx|title=KARIM TO LEAD PAKISTAN\u2019S FIRST-EVER MMA EVENT\n|publisher=Hamari Web}}</ref> Brave 17 took place in [[Lahore]] and saw the emergence of Abdoul Abdouraguimov as a title contender, with the French-Russian submission specialist dominating veteran Rodrigo Cavalheiro en route to a unanimous decision victory<ref>{{cite web|url=https://conandaily.com/2018/10/09/brave-17-pakistan-results-rodrigo-cavalheiro-vs-abdoul-abdouraguimov-jeremy-pacatiw-vs-uloomi-karim/|title=\u2018Brave 17: Pakistan\u2019 results: Rodrigo Cavalheiro vs Abdoul Abdouraguimov, Jeremy Pacatiw vs Uloomi Karim|publisher=Conan Daily}}</ref>\n\n======International Combat Week 2018======\nThe second edition of the International Combat Week, which culminated with Brave 18, was scheduled between November 12 and November 17, with the promotion's return to [[Bahrain]] coming on November 16.\n\nBrave 18 was initially scheduled with three title fights, a first in company history. The Lightweight division would have a new champion after Ottman Azaitar's departure, Bantamweight kingpin Stephen Loman would look to defend his crown once again, while Velimurad Alkhasov and Marcel Adur would fight for the inaugural Flyweight crown<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mixedmartialarts.com/editorial/3-title-fights-at-brave-18-in-bahrain-on-11-16:b5243ff3-8a1b-4bdf-948c-8a732ceddbdb|title=3 title fights at Brave 18 in Bahrain on 11/16|publisher=Mixed Martial Arts}}</ref>\n\nIn the main event of the evening, Abdul-Kareem Al-Selwady stopped Lucas \"Mineiro\" Martins, then interim champion, and unified the Lightweight championship,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/11/16/18098889/brave-cf-18-results-abdul-kareem-al-selwady-dethrones-lucas-martins-stephen-loman-defends-title|title=Brave CF 18 results: Abdul-Kareem Al-Selwady dethrones Lucas Martins, Stephen Loman defends title|publisher=MMA Fighting}}</ref> which was vacated earlier in the year due to inactivity by Ottman Azaitar.\n\nBantamweight champion Stephen Loman became the first titleholder to defend his crown twice for Brave as he beat Brazil's Felipe Efrain by decision in the co-main event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/11/16/18098889/brave-cf-18-results-abdul-kareem-al-selwady-dethrones-lucas-martins-stephen-loman-defends-title|title=Brave CF 18 results: Abdul-Kareem Al-Selwady dethrones Lucas Martins, Stephen Loman defends title|publisher=MMA Fighting}}</ref>\n\nThe Flyweight division remained without a champion, as Velimurad Alkhasov beat Marcel Adur via unanimous decision. Since the Russian powerhouse missed weight, the title would only be up for grabs in case of a win for Adur<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightbookmma.com/alkhasov-misses-weight-for-world-title-fight-at-brave-18/|title=Alkhasov misses weight for world title fight at Brave 18|publisher=Fightbook MMA}}</ref>\n\nThe event was attended by a host of big names such as [[Khabib Nurmagomedov]], Jose \"Shorty\" Torres, Lenne Hardt and [[Sean O'Malley (fighter)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightmag.com.au/2018/11/18/khabib-nurmagomedov-attends-brave-18/|title=UFC LIGHTWEIGHT CHAMP KHABIB NURMAGOMEDOV ATTENDS BRAVE 18 BAHRAIN|publisher=Fightmag}}</ref>\n\n======Busiest month======\nDecember 2018 was the busiest month in the promotion's short history. Brave organized three events in three different countries, with a total of 12 shows in 12 nations for 2018.\n\nBrave 19 took place on December 8, in [[Sun City, North West|Sun City]], [[South Africa]], another country which hosted an international MMA show for the first time with Brave Combat Federation<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/chipfumbu-to-hussein-hes-coming-into-the-jungle-at-brave-19-18369653|title=Chipfumbu to Hussein: He\u2019s coming into the jungle at Brave 19|publisher=IOL}}</ref>\n\nIn the main event, South African prospect Mark Hulme beat American veteran Adam Townsend by unanimous decision, in a violent bout, marked by a cut in Townsend's scalp, coming from an elbow from his opponent<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2018/12/12/18137957/brave-cf-adam-townsend-deep-scalp-cut-decision-loss-mma-news|title=Pic: Brave CF\u2019s Adam Townsend shows deep scalp cut after decision loss in South Africa|publisher=Bloody Elbow}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks later, the promotion made its much-awaited return to [[India]], this time in [[Hyderabad]], where Sidney Wheeler was initially scheduled to take Leon Aliu in the main event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/mma/sidney-wheeler-vs-leon-aliu-to-headline-brave-20|title=Sidney Wheeler vs. Leon Aliu to headline Brave 20|publisher=Sports Keeda}}</ref> However, Aliu was forced to pull out due to injury and was replaced by Khamzat Chimaev.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightbookmma.com/khamzat-chimaev-replaces-leon-aliu-takes-on-sidney-wheeler-at-brave-20/|title=Khamzat Chimaev replaces Leon Aliu, takes on Sidney Wheeler at Brave 20|publisher=Fightbook MMA}}</ref>\n\nThe Swede continued his trend of first-round TKO's by ending Wheeler's night after only 35 seconds, despite having only nine days to prepare for his first main event with Brave.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaviking.com/khamzat-chimaev-quickly-knocks-out-sidney-wheeler-at-brave-20/|title=Khamzat Chimaev quickly knocks out Sidney Wheeler at Brave 20|publisher=MMA Viking}}</ref>\n\nFinally, the year was closed out by another debut country, with [[Saudi Arabia]] also having its first taste of international MMA with Brave 21, which was held in [[Jeddah]], on December 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lovinsaudi.com/lifestyle/sports/saudi-arabias-first-international-mma-fight-will-be-held-tonight-in-jeddah-and-heres-everything-youve-got-to-know-about-it|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s First International MMA Fight Will Be Held Tonight In Jeddah And Here\u2019s Everything You\u2019ve Got To Know About It|publisher=Lovin Saudi}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeremy Kennedy]] continued his string of finishes under Brave as he overwhelmed rising star Marat Magomedov en route to a third-round TKO, in a bout that served as the main event<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mixedmartialarts.com/editorial/brave-21-saudi-arabia-results:e3a339da-fe49-4324-9b68-b7e8f21478f7|title=Brave 21: Saudi Arabia results|publisher=Mixed Martial Arts}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\n\n======Debut in the Philippines======\nWith the success of Bantamweight champion Stephen Loman, Brave announced in November 2018 it would make its debut in the [[Philippines]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://realfight.ph/mma/brave-stage-manila-card-2019/|title=Brave Combat Federation to stage Manila card in 2019|publisher=Real Fight}}</ref> After weeks of speculation, Brave 22 was announced for March 15,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefightnation.com/brave-sets-15-march-for-philippines-debut/|title=BRAVE SETS 15 MARCH FOR PHILIPPINES DEBUT|publisher=The Fight Nation}}</ref> at the [[Mall of Asia Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mixedmartialarts.com/editorial/mall-of-asia-arena-set-to-host-first-ever-brave-event-in-the-philippines:66cb2469-69b2-40fc-b107-ba37498a5ba4|title=Mall of Asia Arena set to host first-ever Brave event in the Philippines|publisher=Mixed Martial Arts}}</ref>\n\nThe show featured the third title defense of Loman's title, as he took on former Featherweight champion Elias Boudegzdame, dropping down to Bantamweight for the first time under Brave.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/1/17/18186807/stephen-loman-defend-brave-title-former-champion-elias-boudegzdame|title=Stephen Loman set to defend Brave title vs. former champ Elias Boudegzdame in March|publisher=MMA Fighting}}</ref>\n\nThe show would initially feature the debut of amateur world champion Jose Torres, who would take on Amir Albazi in the co-main event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://asiamma.com/news-2/breaking-news/jose-shorty-torres-to-make-brave-debut-in-manila/|title=Jose \"Shorty\" Torres to make Brave debut in Manila|publisher=Asia MMA}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the American fighter was forced to withdraw due to injury and the bout was moved to Brave 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefightnation.com/jose-torres-out-of-brave-22-with-injury/|title=JOSE TORRES OUT OF BRAVE 22 WITH INJURY|publisher=The Fight Nation}}</ref>\n\nIn the main event, Loman maintained his undefeated Brave record with another dominant performance, knocking out Boudegzdame in the fourth round of their championship bout<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/sports/2019/03/17/1902217/stephen-loman-leads-pinoy-success-brave-22|title=Stephen Loman leads Pinoy success in Brave 22|publisher=Philstar}}</ref>\n\n======Return to Jordan and Super Lightweight debut======\nBrave 23: Pride and Honor took place on April 19, in [[Amman]], [[Jordan]], and the biggest story was the inauguration of the Super Lightweight division, with a title fight between Eldar Eldarov and Mounir Lazzez<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-23-eldarov-and-lazzez-to-fight-for-inaugural-super-lightweight-title/|title=Brave 23: Eldarov and Lazzez to fight for inaugural Super Lightweight title|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref>\n\nAside from that, Brave 23 also featured another two title fights, with the main event happening between Welterweight champion Jarrah Al-Selawe and challenger Abdoul Abdouraguimov. The bout was also the official start of the Welterweight division as a 175lbs weight class<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/11/28/18116279/brave-adopt-new-165-175-pound-weight-classes-2019-mma|title=Brave to adopt two new weight classes next year, end 170-pound division|publisher=MMA Fighting}}</ref>\n\nFinally, Lightweight world champion Abdul-Kareem Al-Selwady would look to defend his title against Luan \"Miau\" Santiago, who was fresh off a decision victory against Djamil Chan<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmapremium.com.br/luan-miau-desafia-campeao-peso-leve-no-brave-23/|title=Luan \"Miau\" desafia campe\u00e3o peso leve no Brave 23|publisher=MMA Premium}}</ref>\n\nIn the main event, Abdouraguimov won a split decision to become the new Welterweight world champion in a very closely contested bout<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmaonice.com/2019/04/21/brave-23-recap-an-event-not-to-be-forgotten/|title=Brave 23 Recap: An Event Not To Be Forgotten|publisher=MMA on Ice}}</ref>\n\nEldarov became the first-ever Super Lightweight champion with a decision victory over Mounir Lazzez,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://powcastsports.com/eldarov-brings-glory-to-bahrain-with-first-brave-world-title/|title=ELDAROV BRINGS GLORY TO BAHRAIN WITH FIRST BRAVE WORLD TITLE|publisher=Powcast Sports}}</ref> and Luan Santiago also knocked Abdul-Kareem Al-Selwady off his throne with a spinning elbow KO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2019/4/23/18512602/video-luan-santiago-scores-gnarly-spinning-elbow-ko-brave-cf-23-regains-155-belt-mma-news|title=Video: Luan Santiago scores gnarly spinning elbow KO at Brave CF 23, wins 155 belt|publisher=Bloody Elbow}}</ref>\n\n======London extravaganza and South America tour======\n\nOn July 25, Brave Combat Federation made its much-anticipated debut in [[London]]. With a seven-fight card in an invite-only show with hundreds of influencers, celebrities, and politicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fightpost.co.uk/2019/07/29/vip-personalities-enchanted-by-brave-24-london-action/|title=VIP Personalities Enchanted by BRAVE 24: London Action|publisher=Fight Post}}</ref> In the main event, [[Bubba Jenkins]] successfully defended his Featherweight title against Brazil's Lucas Mineiro.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2019/07/brave-cf-24-jenkins-vs-martins-live-results|title=Brave CF 24: Bubba Jenkins retains 145-pound title with dominant first-round TKO in London|publisher=MMA Junkie}}</ref>\n\nA little more than a month later, Brave made its annual trip to [[Brazil]], once again hosting an event in [[Belo Horizonte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/8/6/20756707/luan-santiago-cleiton-silva-matheus-nicolau-felipe-efrain-brave-25-brazil-mma|title=Luan Santiago vs. Cleiton Silva will headline Brave 25 in Brazil|publisher=MMA Fighting}}</ref> In the main event, newly-crowned Lightweight world champion Luan Santiago ended up submitted in the first seconds of his bout against Cleiton Silva, who became the fifth Brave CF Lightweight titleholder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tatame.com.br/2019/09/cleiton-predador-finaliza-luan-miau-e-e-coroado-campeao-do-brave-cf-em-minas-matheus-nicolau-estreia-com-vitoria/|title=Cleiton Predador finaliza Luan Miau e \u00e9 coroado campe\u00e3o do BRAVE CF em Minas; Matheus Nicolau estreia com vit\u00f3ria|publisher=Tatame}}</ref>\n\nA week later, Brave returned to Colombia, when former [[UFC]] fighter Felipe Silva made his promotional debut. Silva scored a TKO victory over Dumar Roa, while Luana Pinheiro became the first woman with two Brave CF wins, by submitting Yasmeli Araque also in the first round of Brave 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lowkickmma.com/brave-26-results-silva-earns-tko-victory-over-roa/|title=BRAVE 26 Results: Silva Earns TKO Victory Over Roa|publisher=Low Kick MMA}}</ref>\n\n======KHK World Championships======\n\nAfter successful events in Abu Dhabi and Romania, BRAVE Combat Federation turned its attention to its biggest show ever, which took place on November 15 in Isa Town, Bahrain. BRAVE CF 29 crowned the first-ever KHK World Champion, in a one-night, four-men, openweight tournament, that included Brazilians [[Guto Inocente]] and Kleber Orgulho, as well as Russian powerhouse Azamat Murzakanov and Lebanon superstar Mohammad Fakhreddine. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tatame.com.br/2019/11/brasileiro-kleber-orgulho-se-junta-a-guto-inocente-em-torneio-sem-limite-de-peso-no-bahrein-campeao-fatura-100-mil-dolares/|title=Brasileiro Kleber Orgulho se junta a Guto Inocente em torneio sem limite de peso no Bahrein; campe\u00e3o fatura 100 mil d\u00f3lares|publisher=Tatame}}</ref>.\n\nAfter two fights in one night, Azamat Murzakanov came out victorious. He took home US$100,000, and also became the provisional holder of the KHK belt, the most prestigious prize in sports, weighing 6,2 kg of gold. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://themaclife.com/featured-posts/prestigious-prize-sports-history-brave-cf-introduce-solid-gold-championship-belt/|title=Most prestigious prize in sports history\u2019: BRAVE CF introduce solid gold championship belt|publisher=The Mac Life}}</ref>  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2019/11/brave-cf-29-results-azamat-murzakanov-wins-open-weight-title|title=Brave CF 29 results: Azamat Murzakanov runs through competition to win KHK open weight title|publisher=MMA Junkie}}</ref>\n\n'''Return to India'''\n\nBrave Combat Federation returned to India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lockerroom.in/blog/view/Brave-CF-30-Eight-Indian-Fighters-On-the-Card|title=Brave Combat Federation returns to India with Brave CF 30 {{!}} LockerRoom|last=|first=|date=|website=LockerRoom India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> for Brave CF 30 on November 23, 2019. The event was headlined by the Bantamweight title fight between champion Stephen Loman and Louie Sanoudakis. The card also had a strong presence of Indian fighters as well. Stephen Loman retained the title with a unanimous decision victory in the main event<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lockerroom.in/blog/view/Brave-CF-30-Complete-Results|title=Brave CF 30 Complete Results {{!}} LockerRoom India|last=|first=|date=|website=LockerRoom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\n==Rules==\nBrave Combat Federation follows the ''[[Unified Rules of Mixed Martial Arts]]'' that were originally established by the [[New Jersey State Athletic Control Board]] and modified by the [[Nevada State Athletic Commission]].<ref name=\"nsac\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NAC/NAC-467.html |title=NSAC Regulations: CHAPTER 467 - UNARMED COMBAT |publisher=Nevada State Athletic Commission |accessdate=February 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Association of Boxing Commissions]] approved the opening of new weight classes,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2017/7/26/16037760/abc-approves-adoption-of-four-new-weight-classes-for-mma|title=ABC approves adoption of four new weight classes for MMA - MMA Fighting|publisher=}}</ref> Brave announced it would become the first international promotion to introduce a Super Lightweight division, as well as pushing the Welterweight limit to 175 lbs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mixedmartialarts.com/editorial/brave-announces-new-weight-classes-for-2019:18396f5c-da8c-427c-97a2-4fc8aba8e8f1|title=Brave announces new weight classes for 2019 - Mixed Martial Arts|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Weight divisions and champions==\n{{See also|Mixed martial arts weight classes}}\n\nBrave Combat Federation has following weight classes:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Weight class name\n!colspan=\"2\"|Upper limit\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Current champion\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Date won\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Title Defenses\n|-\n!in [[Pound (mass)|pounds]] (lb)\n!in [[kilogram]]s (kg)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Strawweight (MMA)|Strawweight]]\n|115||52.2||Vacant||-||-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Flyweight (MMA)|Flyweight]]\n|125||56.7||Vacant||-||-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Bantamweight (MMA)|Bantamweight]]\n|135||61.2||{{flagicon|Philippines}} Stephen Loman||November 17, 2017||4\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Featherweight (MMA)|Featherweight]]\n|145||65.8||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Bubba Jenkins]]||July 25, 2019||1\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Lightweight (MMA)|Lightweight]]\n|155||70.3||{{flagicon|BRA}} Cleiton Silva||August 30, 2019||0\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Super lightweight (MMA)|Super Lightweight]]\n|165||74.8||{{flagicon|BHR}} Eldar Eldarov||April 19, 2019||0\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight]]\n|175||79.4||{{flagicon|JOR}} Jarrah Al-Selawe||October 4, 2019||0\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Middleweight (MMA)|Middleweight]]\n|185||83.9||{{flagicon|BRA}} Daniel \"Gaucho\" Souza||December 7, 2019||0\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Light Heavyweight (MMA)|Light Heavyweight]]\n|205||93.0||Vacant||-||-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]]\n|265||120.2||Vacant||-||-\n|}\n\n==Brave Combat Federation Title history==\n\n===Brave Combat Federation Light Heavyweight Championship===\n:''186 to 205 lbs (84.3 to 93 kg)''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!st