er 23, 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n==Brave Combat Federation Records<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/promotions/1782-brave-combat-federation-bcf|title=Brave Combat Federation - BCF - MMA Promoter Page - Tapology|website=Tapology}}</ref>==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Record!!Fighter!!Number\n|-\n|Most Bouts || {{flagicon|PHI}} Jeremy Pacatiw || 10\n|-\n|Most Wins || {{flagicon|JOR}} Jarrah Al-Selawe || 7\n|-\n|Most Total Fight Time  || {{flagicon|PHI}} Jeremy Pacatiw || 118:09\n|-\n|Most Knockouts || {{flagicon|LBN}} Mohammad Fakhreddine {{flagicon|RUS}} Ikram Aliskerov || 4\n|-\n|Fastest Knockout || {{flagicon|NED}} Djamil Chan || 0:29\n|-\n|Most Submissions || {{flagicon|Algeria}} Elias Boudegzdame {{flagicon|BRA}} Klidson de Abreu || 3\n|-\n|Fastest Submission || {{flagicon|PAK}} Mehmosh Raza || 0:23\n|}\n\n==Broadcast==\n\n===TV partners===\n* [[Bahrain Radio and Television Corporation]]\n* [[OSN Sports]]\n* [[El Rey Network]]\n* [[Abu Dhabi Sports]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bahrainthisweek.com/brave-18-breaks-record-for-broadcasting-reach/|title=Brave 18 breaks record for broadcasting reach|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Globosat|Combate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lance.com.br/lutas/ufc-fight-night-abu-dhabi-world-pro-brave-agitam-combate.html|title=UFC Fight Night, Abu Dhabi World Pro e Brave 5 agitam o Combate|website=www.lance.com.br}}</ref>\n* [[Myx TV]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myxtv.com/shows/brave-combat-federation|title=Myx TV - Brave Combat Federation|publisher=|access-date=2017-02-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224053659/http://myxtv.com/shows/brave-combat-federation|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action|S+A]]\n* [[ESPN 5]]\n* [[MTV India]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/media/entertainment/mtv-mercury-sports-sign-multi-year-deal-to-bring-brave-fights-reality-show-on-tv/articleshow/67157002.cms|title=MTV, Mercury Sports sign multi-year deal to bring Brave fights, reality show on TV|accessdate=December 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* Fite TV<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fite.tv/vl/p/brave-combat-federation/|title=Brave Combat Federation Streams & Videos|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===BRAVE TV===\n\nBrave Combat Federation announced last year the creation of BRAVE TV, an online subscription service in which fans would be able to watch live events, as well as reruns of old shows. Brave 23 was available on the newly-formed online streaming platform to fans from all over the world, except for those territories contemplated with preexisting TV deals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bravefights.com/brave-combat-federation-to-live-stream-historical-jordan-event-for-free/|title=BRAVE COMBAT FEDERATION TO LIVE STREAM HISTORICAL JORDAN EVENT FOR FREE|publisher=BRAVE Fights}}</ref>\n\n===Talents===\n* [[Cyrus Fees]]: Play-by-play commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravefights.com/cyrus-fees-is-confirmed-as-brave-1-official-announcer/|title=Cyrus Fees is confirmed as Brave 1 official announcer - BRAVE Fights|website=www.bravefights.com}}</ref>\n* [[Frankie Edgar]]: Color Commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/mma/mma-news-frankie-edgar-to-be-color-commentator-for-brave-3|title=MMA News: Frankie Edgar to commentate at Brave 3|date=22 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Nate Quarry]]: Color Commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wn.com/brave_6_kazakhstan_breakdown_with_nate_rock_quarry|title=Brave 6 Kazakhstan Breakdown With Nate Rock Quarry|website=World News}}</ref>\n* Alex Soto: Color Commentator\n* Phil Campbell: Color Commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmauk.net/2018/09/13/brave-combat-federation-signs-tv-talent-from-belfast/|title=Brave Combat Federation signs TV talent from Belfast|publisher=MMA UK}}</ref>\n* Carlos Kremer: Cage announcer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravefights.com/brave-confirms-carlos-kremer-as-cage-announcer/|title=Brave confirms Carlos Kremer as cage announcer - BRAVE Fights|website=www.bravefights.com}}</ref>\n* [[Cristiane Justino|Cris Cyborg]]: Guest commentator\n* Noel O'Keefe<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmacharge.com/noel-okeeffe-to-join-brave-commentary-team-in-abu-dhabi/|title=Noel O\u2019Keeffe to join Brave commentary team in Abu Dhabi|publisher=MMA Charge}}</ref>\n* Kirik Jenness<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdnonline.com/Details/320154/MMA-expert-Jenness-joins-Brave-commentary-panel|title=MMA expert Jenness joins Brave commentary panel|publisher=Gulf Daily News}}</ref>\n\n==Film Production==\n===SMILE - Documentary===\n[[File:Poster_of_SMILE.jpg|thumb|right|Poster of SMILE]]\nBrave Combat Federation has announced initiation of operations of their subsidiary film production unit named Brave Films. To commence operations the film production unit produced the television documentary-drama \"SMILE\"<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7074622/</ref> on 26 June during Eid.<ref>http://www.gdnonline.com/Details/220315/Brave-launch-SMILE-trailer</ref> The documentary narrates the story of the featherweight champion of Brave Combat Federation and behind the scenes of his training leading to the championship bout. The content was shot extensively in [[Montpellier]], France and Tijuana, Mexico apart from locations in Bahrain and in [[Abu Dhabi]], United Arab Emirates. The initiative was publicised to popularise mixed martial arts and to showcase the lifestyle of fighters<ref>http://thefangarage.com/articles/11097-brave-launches-trailer-for-documentary-based-on-the-life-of-elias-boudegezdane</ref> and marks the launch of \u201cBrave Films\u201d, a film production segment by Brave Combat Federation.<ref>http://www.arabsmma.com/trailer-mma-film-smile-boudegzdame/</ref>\n\n==BRAVE International Combat Week==\nIn February 2017, KHK MMA and [[IMMAF]] announced, during a press conference, a partnership which would see the Amateur World Championships move from [[Las Vegas]] to [[Bahrain]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://immaf.org/event/2017-immaf-world-championships/|title=2017 IMMAF World Championships|publisher=IMMAF}}</ref>\n\n[[IMMAF]] president [[Kerrith Brown]] was present at the official announcement, in which Bahrain MMA Association president Khalid Abdulaziz Al Khayyat praised Sheikh [[Khalid bin Hamad Al Khalifa]]'s commitment to creating a culture for mixed martial arts in the region and claimed this shift as a deal closer for the world championships to move to Bahrain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/mma/mma-news-bahrain-to-host-2017-immaf-world-championships-of-amateur-mma|title=MMA News: Bahrain to host 2017 IMMAF World Championships of Amateur MMA|publisher=Sports Keeda}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the world championships, BRAVE president [[Mohammed \"The Hawk\" Shahid]] announced in the same press conference that the promotion would host a show in the same week as the World Championships, saying it would be \"one of the biggest fight weeks we've seen in Middle East combat sports history\", which was named International Combat Week<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=67&v=ECgGumM4-Nk|title=KHK MMA CEO confirms IMMAF World Championship during International Combat Week|publisher=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOrganized under the patronage of His Highness Sheikh [[Nasser bin Hamad Al Khalifa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizbahrain.com/brave-international-combat-week-starts/|title=BRAVE International Combat Week starts|publisher=Biz Bahrain}}</ref> the first International Combat Week was held from November 12 to November 19, with BRAVE 9 taking place on November 17, featuring two title fights.\n\n===2018===\nIn March 2018, [[IMMAF]] president [[Kerrith Brown]] officially announced the return of the Amateur World Championships to Bahrain for 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://immaf.org/2018-2019-immaf-world-championships-announced-for-bahrain-2/|title=2018 & 2019 IMMAF WORLD CHAMPIONSHIPS ANNOUNCED FOR BAHRAIN|publisher=IMMAF}}</ref>\n\nThe 2018 International Combat Week took place between November 11 and November 18, with BRAVE 18 taking place on November 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bna.bh/en/BRAVEInternationalCombatWeekwillcementBahrainsinternationalposition.aspx?cms=q8FmFJgiscL2fwIzON1%2BDgJ1toQfYlLVqhxjrhg9TpA%3D|title=BRAVE International Combat Week will cement Bahrain's international position|publisher=Bahrain News Agency}}</ref>\n\nBRAVE 18 crowned a new Lightweight champion in Abdul-Kareem Al-Selwady, and Stephen Loman retained his Bantamweight title by defending it against Brazil's Felipe Efrain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabsmma.com/brave-18-results-al-selwady-destroys-x-ufc-fighter-to-become-brave-world-champion/|title=Brave 18 Results: Al-Selwady destroys X-UFC fighter to become Brave world champion|publisher=Arabs MMA}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of current Brave CF fighters]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MMA organizations}}\n\n[[Category:Mixed martial arts organizations]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial arts television programs]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brave_Combat_Federation"}
{"title_page": "Brake fluid", "text_new": "'''Brake fluid''' is a type of [[hydraulic fluid]] used in [[hydraulic brake]] and [[Clutch|hydraulic clutch]] applications in [[automobile]]s, [[motorcycle]]s, [[light truck]]s, and some [[bicycle]]s. It is used to transfer force into pressure, and to [[Pascals law#Explanation|amplify]] braking force. It works because [[liquid#Mechanical properties|liquid]]s are not appreciably [[compression (physical)|compressible]].\n\nMost brake fluids used today are [[Glycol ethers|glycol-ether]] based, but [[mineral oil]] (''[[Citro\u00ebn]]/[[Rolls-Royce Motor Cars|Rolls-Royce]] liquide hydraulique min\u00e9ral'' ([[Hydropneumatic suspension#LHS versus LHM|LHM]])) and [[silicone]]-based (DOT 5) fluids are also available.<ref >{{cite web|url=http://www.peterverdone.com/archive/files/hydraulic%20system%20theory.pdf|format=PDF|title=Chapter 7 : Basic Hydraulic System Theory|website=Peterverdone.com|accessdate=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==Standards==\nBrake fluids must meet certain requirements as defined by various standards set by international, national, or local organizations or government agencies.  \n\n===International===\nThe [[International Standards Organisation]] has published its standard ISO 4925, defining classes 3, 4, and 5, as well as class 5.1 and class 6,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iso.org/standard/38513.html|title=ISO 4925:2005 - Road vehicles -- Specification of non-petroleum-base brake fluids for hydraulic systems|website=www.iso.org}}</ref> reflecting progressively higher performance for brake fluids.\n\n===United States===\nThe [[Society of Automotive Engineers]] SAE has published standards J1703, J1704, and J1705, reflecting progressively higher performance for brake fluids.   These have counterparts in the international standard, ISO 4925.\n\nMost brake fluid sold in North America is classified by the US [[Department of Transportation]] (DOT) under its own ratings such as \"DOT 3\" and \"DOT 4\" and these are widely used in other countries. Their classifications broadly reflect the SAE's specifications, but with local details \u2014 [[Alaska]] and the [[Azores]] for example, have different normal temperature and humidity ranges to consider.  DOT 3 is equivalent to SAE J1703 and ISO class 3, DOT 4 to SAE J1704 and ISO class 4, etc.<ref name=standards>{{cite web|url=https://wiki.anton-paar.com/en/automotive-brake-fluids/|title=Viscosity of Automotive Brake Fluids|publisher=Anton Paar Wiki|accessdate=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\nAll approved fluids must be colorless or amber to be acceptable for street use in the U.S, except for DOT 5 silicone, which must be purple.{{cn|date=April 2018}}\n\n==== DOT 4 ====\nWhile a vehicle that uses DOT 3 may also use DOT 4 or 5.1 if the elastomers in the system accept the borate compounds that raise the boiling point,{{fact|date=January 2013}} (a temperature upgrade) a vehicle that requires DOT 4 might boil the brake fluid if a DOT 3 (a temperature downgrade) is used. Additionally, these [[polyglycol ether|polyglycol-ether]]-based fluids cannot be mixed with DOT 5.0, which is silicone based.\n\n{{As of|2006}}, most cars produced in the U.S. use DOT 4 brake fluid.\n\n==== DOT 5 ====\nDOT 5 is a silicone-based fluid and is separate from the series of DOT 2, 3, 4, 5.1. It is immiscible with water, and with other brake fluids, and must not be mixed with them. Systems can change fluid only after a complete system changeover, such as a total restoration.\n\nIt contains at least 70% by weight of a diorgano polysiloxane.<ref >[http://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/rules-regulations/administration/fmcsr/fmcsrruletext.asp?section=571.116 Standard No. 116; Motor vehicle brake fluids Code of Federal Regulations, Title 49 - Transportation, Chapter V - Part 571 - Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards (49CFR571), Subpart B, Sec. 571.116 Standard No. 116; Motor vehicle brake fluids]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208235145/http://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/rules-regulations/administration/fmcsr/fmcsrruletext.asp?section=571.116 |date=2008-12-08\n}}</ref> Unlike polyethylene glycol based fluids, DOT 5 is [[hydrophobic]].<ref >{{cite web |url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/auto-parts/brakes/brake-parts/types-of-brake-fluid.htm |title=What are the different types of brake fluid? |work=How Stuff Works |date=2008-12-01 |access-date=2018-08-12}}</ref> An advantage over other forms of brake fluid is that silicone has a more stable viscosity index over a wider temperature range. Another property is that it does not damage paint.{{citation needed |date=March 2013}} \n\nDOT 5 brake fluid is not compatible with [[anti-lock braking system]]s. DOT 5 fluid can aerate when the anti-lock brake system is activated. DOT 5 brake fluid absorbs a small amount of air requiring care when bleeding the system of air.<ref >{{cite web|url=http://www.freeasestudyguides.com/dot-5-brake-fluid.html|title=DOT 5 Brake Fluid: Not for ABS|website=www.freeasestudyguides.com}}</ref>\n\nLack of acceptance of silicone-based fluids led to the development of DOT 5.1, a fluid giving the performance advantages of silicone, whilst retaining some familiarity and compatibility with the glycol ester fluids.\n\n=== Citro\u00ebn hydropneumatic suspension ===\nIn the 1950s, Citro\u00ebn introduced a [[hydropneumatic suspension]] system, powered by an engine-driven pump and also used to operate the braking system. This used a Citro\u00ebn-specific hydraulic fluid. The first fluid was [[LHS (hydraulic fluid)|LHS]], a vegetable oil-based fluid. This was later replaced by [[LHM (hydraulic fluid)|LHM]], a mineral fluid. LHS was hygroscopic and gave problems with internal corrosion. Although the two fluids are incompatible, LHM has been universal since 1967, and most older cars have been converted to use it.\n\nThis system was also used on Rolls-Royce and some Maserati models.\n\n=== Hydragas and Hydrolastic suspension ===\n[[Hydragas]] and [[Hydrolastic]] suspension were a widely used form of hydropneumatic suspension, designed by [[Alex Moulton]], and used on [[British Leyland]] cars from the 1960s. This system was not engine-driven and did not involve the braking system. \n\nThe fluid was a low viscosity fluid based on diluted alcohol.<ref >{{Cite web\n  |title=Hydragas suspension technical data\n  |website=Hydragas Register\n  |url=http://www.hydragas.co.uk/technical.html\n}}</ref>\n:    49% alcohol\n:    49% distilled water\n:    1% [[triethanolamine]] phosphate  (surfactant)\n:    1% sodium [[mercaptobenzothiazole]] (stenching agent)\n\n==Characteristics==\nBrake fluids must have certain characteristics and meet certain quality standards for the braking system to work properly.\n\n===Viscosity===\nFor reliable, consistent brake system operation, brake fluid must maintain a constant viscosity under a wide range of temperatures, including extreme cold. This is especially important in systems with an [[anti-lock braking system]] (ABS), [[traction control]], and [[stability control]] (ESP), as these systems often use micro-valves and require very rapid activation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.partinfo.co.uk/articles/63|title=Brake Fluid Exchange and Technology|website=Partinfo.co.uk|accessdate=2018-05-16}}</ref>  DOT 5.1 fluids are specified with low viscosity over a wide range of temperatures, although not all cars fitted with ABS or ESP specify DOT 5.1 brake fluid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trwaftermarket.com/en/passenger-cars-and-lcv/actuation-systems/brake-fluid/|title=Brake Fluid|website=Trwaftermarket.com|accessdate=2018-05-26}}</ref>\nEven more car factory provides or recommends for a faster reaction of the ABS and ESP systems the DOT 4 LV (low viscosity) brake fluids.\nThe specific V100 value of this products 1,50 - 2,00 mm2/sec.\n\n===Boiling point===\nBrake fluid is subjected to very high temperatures, especially in the [[wheel cylinder]]s of [[drum brake]]s and [[disk brake]] calipers. It must have a high boiling point to avoid vaporizing in the lines. This vaporization creates a problem because vapor is highly compressible relative to liquid, and therefore negates the hydraulic transfer of braking force - so the brakes will fail to stop the vehicle.<ref name=epic>{{cite web|url=http://www.epicbleedsolutions.com/blog/dot-brake-fluid-vs-mineral-oil/|title=DOT Brake Fluid vs. Mineral Oil|website=Epicbleedsolutions.com|accessdate=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\nQuality standards refer to a brake fluid's \"dry\" and \"wet\" boiling points. The wet boiling point, which is usually much lower (although above most normal service temperatures), refers to the fluid's boiling point after absorbing a certain amount of moisture. This is several (single digit) percent, varying from formulation to formulation. Glycol-ether (DOT 3, 4, and 5.1) brake fluids are [[Hygroscopy|hygroscopic]] (water absorbing), which means they absorb moisture from the atmosphere under normal humidity levels.  Non-hygroscopic fluids (e.g. [[silicone]]/DOT 5 and mineral oil based formulations), are [[hydrophobic]], and can maintain an acceptable boiling point over the fluid's service life.\n\nSilicone based fluid is more compressible than glycol based fluid, leading to brakes with a ''spongy'' feeling.<ref name=epic/> It can potentially suffer phase separation/water pooling and freezing/boiling in the system over time - the main reason single phase hygroscopic fluids are used.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Characteristics of common braking fluids<ref name=\"DOT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/granule/CFR-2011-title49-vol6/CFR-2011-title49-vol6-sec571-116|title=49 CFR 571.116 - Standard No. 116; Motor vehicle brake fluids.|website=Gpo.gov|accessdate=2018-07-06}}</ref><ref name=epic/>\n|-\n!\n! Dry [[boiling point]]\n! Wet boiling point{{efn|\"Wet\" defined as 3.7% water by volume}}\n! Viscosity limit\n! Primary constituent\n|-\n| DOT 2 || {{convert|190|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|140|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || ? || castor oil/alcohol\n|-\n| DOT 3 || {{convert|205|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|140|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 1500 {{mm2}}/s || [[Glycol ethers|glycol ether]]\n|-\n| DOT 4  || {{convert|230|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|155|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 1800 {{mm2}}/s || glycol ether/[[borate ester]]\n|-\n| [[Hydropneumatic suspension#LHS versus LHM|LHM+]] || {{convert|249|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|249|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 1200 {{mm2}}/s <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viscopedia.com/viscosity-tables/substances/automotive-brake-fluid/|title=Viscosity of Automotive brake fluid \u2013 viscosity table and viscosity chart :: Anton Paar Wiki|website=Anton Paar|accessdate=2018-07-06}}</ref> || mineral oil\n|-\n| DOT 5 || {{convert|260|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|180|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 900 {{mm2}}/s || silicone\n|-\n| DOT 5.1 || {{convert|260|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|180|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 900 {{mm2}}/s || glycol ether/borate ester\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Corrosion===\nBrake fluids must not corrode the metals used inside components such as calipers, wheel cylinders, master cylinders and ABS control valves. They must also protect against corrosion as moisture enters the system. Additives (corrosion inhibitors) are added to the base fluid to accomplish this. Silicone is less corrosive to paintwork unlike glycol-ether based DOT fluids.<ref name=epic/>\n\nThe advantage of the Citro\u00ebn LHM mineral oil based brake fluid is the absence of corrosion. Seals may wear out at high mileages but otherwise these systems have exceptional longevity. It cannot be used as a substitute without changing seals due to incompatibility with the rubber.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xpowerforums.com/Brake_Fluidsl_FA_Questions.htm|title=AN EXPLANATION OF BRAKE AND CLUTCH FLUIDS|website=Xpowerforums.com|accessdate=2015-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Compressibility===\nBrake fluids must maintain a low level of compressibility, even with varying temperatures to accommodate different environmental conditions. This is important to ensure consistent brake pedal feel. As compressibility increases, more brake pedal travel is necessary for the same amount of brake caliper piston force.\n\n==Service and maintenance==\n\nGlycol-ether (DOT 3, 4, and 5.1) brake fluids are hygroscopic (water absorbing), which means they absorb moisture from the atmosphere under normal humidity levels. Non-hygroscopic fluids (e.g. silicone/DOT 5 and mineral oil based formulations), are hydrophobic, and can maintain an acceptable boiling point over the fluid's service life. Ideally, silicone fluid should be used only to fill non-ABS systems that have not been previously filled with glycol based fluid. Any system that has used glycol-based fluid (DOT 3/4/5.1) will contain moisture; glycol fluid disperses the moisture throughout the system and contains corrosion inhibitors. Silicone fluid does not allow moisture to enter the system, but does not disperse any that is already there, either. A system filled from dry with silicone fluid does not require the fluid to be changed at intervals, only when the system has been disturbed for a component repair or renewal. The United States armed forces have standardised on silicone brake fluid since the 1990s. Silicone fluid is used extensively in cold climates, particularly in Russia and Finland.\n\nBrake fluids with different DOT ratings can not always be mixed. DOT 5 should not be mixed with any of the others as mixing of glycol with silicone fluid may cause corrosion because of trapped moisture.  DOT 2 should not be mixed with any of the others.  DOT 3, DOT 4, and DOT 5.1 are all based on glycol esters and can be mixed, although it is preferable to completely replace existing fluids with fresh to obtain the specified performance.\n\nBrake fluid is toxic<ref name=\"toxicity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.online.petro-canada.ca/datasheets/en_CA/w449.pdf|title=MSDS for DOT 3 brake fluid|website=Online.petro-canada.ca|accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref> and can damage painted surfaces.<ref name=\"Paint damage by Brake Fluid\">{{cite web|url=http://www.totalmotorcycle.com/maintenance/generaltips.htm|title=General Tips|publisher=Total Motorcycle|accessdate=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\n==Components==\n=== Castor oil-based (pre-DOT, DOT 2) ===\n* [[Castor oil]]\n* [[Alcohol]], usually [[butanol]] (red / crimson fluid) or [[ethanol]] (yellow fluid) (methanol)\n\n===Glycol-based (DOT 3, 4, 5.1)===\n* [[Alkyl ester]]\n* [[Aliphatic]] [[amine]]\n* [[Diethylene glycol]]\n* [[Diethylene glycol monoethyl ether]]\n* [[Diethylene glycol monomethyl ether]]\n* [[Dimethyl dipropylene glycol]]\n* [[Polyethylene glycol monobutyl ether]]\n* [[Polyethylene glycol monomethyl ether]]\n* [[Polyethylene oxide]]\n* [[Triethylene glycol monobutyl ether]]\n* [[Triethylene glycol monoethyl ether]]\n* [[Triethylene glycol monomethyl ether]]\n\n===Silicone-based (DOT 5)===\n* [[Dioctyl sebacate|Di-2-ethylhexyl sebacate]]\n* [[Dimethyl polysiloxane]]\n* [[Tributyl phosphate]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hydropneumatic]]\n* [[Pascal's law]]\n*[[Brake fluid pressure sensor]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070304074607/http://www.carcare.org/Brakes/brake_fluid.shtml Car care council]\n* [http://auto.howstuffworks.com/auto-parts/brakes/brake-parts/types-of-brake-fluid.htm ''How Stuff Works: What are the different types of brake fluid?'']\n* [http://www.stoptech.com/tech_info/wp_brakefluid_1a.shtml StopTech: Brake Fluid 1A]\n\n{{Motor fuel}}\n{{Powertrain}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brake Fluid}}\n[[Category:Vehicle braking technologies]]\n[[Category:Automotive chemicals]]\n[[Category:Hydraulic fluids]]\n", "text_old": "'''Brake fluid''' is a type of [[hydraulic fluid]] used in [[hydraulic brake]] and [[Clutch|hydraulic clutch]] applications in [[automobile]]s, [[motorcycle]]s, [[light truck]]s, and some [[bicycle]]s. It is used to transfer force into pressure, and to [[Pascals law#Explanation|amplify]] braking force. It works because [[liquid#Mechanical properties|liquid]]s are not appreciably [[compression (physical)|compressible]].\n\nMost brake fluids used today are [[Glycol ethers|glycol-ether]] based, but [[mineral oil]] (''[[Citro\u00ebn]]/[[Rolls-Royce Motor Cars|Rolls-Royce]] liquide hydraulique min\u00e9ral'' ([[Hydropneumatic suspension#LHS versus LHM|LHM]])) and [[silicone]]-based (DOT 5) fluids are also available.<ref >{{cite web|url=http://www.peterverdone.com/archive/files/hydraulic%20system%20theory.pdf|format=PDF|title=Chapter 7 : Basic Hydraulic System Theory|website=Peterverdone.com|accessdate=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==Standards==\nBrake fluids must meet certain requirements as defined by various standards set by international, national, or local organizations or government agencies.  \n\n===International===\nThe [[International Standards Organisation]] has published its standard ISO 4925, defining classes 3, 4, and 5, as well as class 5.1 and class 6,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iso.org/standard/38513.html|title=ISO 4925:2005 - Road vehicles -- Specification of non-petroleum-base brake fluids for hydraulic systems|website=www.iso.org}}</ref> reflecting progressively higher performance for brake fluids.\n\n===United States===\nThe [[Society of Automotive Engineers]] SAE has published standards J1703, J1704, and J1705, reflecting progressively higher performance for brake fluids.   These have counterparts in the international standard, ISO 4925.\n\nMost brake fluid sold in North America is classified by the US [[Department of Transportation]] (DOT) under its own ratings such as \"DOT 3\" and \"DOT 4\" and these are widely used in other countries. Their classifications broadly reflect the SAE's specifications, but with local details \u2014 [[Alaska]] and the [[Azores]] for example, have different normal temperature and humidity ranges to consider.  DOT 3 is equivalent to SAE J1703 and ISO class 3, DOT 4 to SAE J1704 and ISO class 4, etc.<ref name=standards>{{cite web|url=https://wiki.anton-paar.com/en/automotive-brake-fluids/|title=Viscosity of Automotive Brake Fluids|publisher=Anton Paar Wiki|accessdate=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\nAll approved fluids must be colorless or amber to be acceptable for street use in the U.S, except for DOT 5 silicone, which must be purple.{{cn|date=April 2018}}\n\n==== DOT 4 ====\nWhile a vehicle that uses DOT 3 may also use DOT 4 or 5.1 if the elastomers in the system accept the borate compounds that raise the boiling point,{{fact|date=January 2013}} (a temperature upgrade) a vehicle that requires DOT 4 might boil the brake fluid if a DOT 3 (a temperature downgrade) is used. Additionally, these [[polyglycol ether|polyglycol-ether]]-based fluids cannot be mixed with DOT 5.0, which is silicone based.\n\n{{As of|2006}}, most cars produced in the U.S. use DOT 4 brake fluid.\n\n==== DOT 5 ====\nDOT 5 is a silicone-based fluid and is separate from the series of DOT 2, 3, 4, 5.1. It is immiscible with water, and with other brake fluids, and must not be mixed with them. Systems can change fluid only after a complete system changeover, such as a total restoration.\n\nIt contains at least 70% by weight of a diorgano polysiloxane<ref >[http://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/rules-regulations/administration/fmcsr/fmcsrruletext.asp?section=571.116 Standard No. 116; Motor vehicle brake fluids Code of Federal Regulations, Title 49 - Transportation, Chapter V - Part 571 - Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards (49CFR571), Subpart B, Sec. 571.116 Standard No. 116; Motor vehicle brake fluids]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208235145/http://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/rules-regulations/administration/fmcsr/fmcsrruletext.asp?section=571.116 |date=2008-12-08\n}}</ref>. Unlike polyethylene glycol based fluids, DOT 5 is [[hydrophobic]].<ref >{{cite web |url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/auto-parts/brakes/brake-parts/types-of-brake-fluid.htm |title=What are the different types of brake fluid? |work=How Stuff Works |date=2008-12-01 |access-date=2018-08-12}}</ref> An advantage over other forms of brake fluid is that silicone has a more stable viscosity index over a wider temperature range. Another property is that it does not damage paint.{{citation needed |date=March 2013}} \n\nDOT 5 brake fluid is not compatible with [[anti-lock braking system]]s. DOT 5 fluid can aerate when the anti-lock brake system is activated. DOT 5 brake fluid absorbs a small amount of air requiring care when bleeding the system of air.<ref >{{cite web|url=http://www.freeasestudyguides.com/dot-5-brake-fluid.html|title=DOT 5 Brake Fluid: Not for ABS|website=www.freeasestudyguides.com}}</ref>\n\nLack of acceptance of silicone-based fluids led to the development of DOT 5.1, a fluid giving the performance advantages of silicone, whilst retaining some familiarity and compatibility with the glycol ester fluids.\n\n=== Citro\u00ebn hydropneumatic suspension ===\nIn the 1950s, Citro\u00ebn introduced a [[hydropneumatic suspension]] system, powered by an engine-driven pump and also used to operate the braking system. This used a Citro\u00ebn-specific hydraulic fluid. The first fluid was [[LHS (hydraulic fluid)|LHS]], a vegetable oil-based fluid. This was later replaced by [[LHM (hydraulic fluid)|LHM]], a mineral fluid. LHS was hygroscopic and gave problems with internal corrosion. Although the two fluids are incompatible, LHM has been universal since 1967, and most older cars have been converted to use it.\n\nThis system was also used on Rolls-Royce and some Maserati models.\n\n=== Hydragas and Hydrolastic suspension ===\n[[Hydragas]] and [[Hydrolastic]] suspension were a widely used form of hydropneumatic suspension, designed by [[Alex Moulton]], and used on [[British Leyland]] cars from the 1960s. This system was not engine-driven and did not involve the braking system. \n\nThe fluid was a low viscosity fluid based on diluted alcohol.<ref >{{Cite web\n  |title=Hydragas suspension technical data\n  |website=Hydragas Register\n  |url=http://www.hydragas.co.uk/technical.html\n}}</ref>\n:    49% alcohol\n:    49% distilled water\n:    1% [[triethanolamine]] phosphate  (surfactant)\n:    1% sodium [[mercaptobenzothiazole]] (stenching agent)\n\n==Characteristics==\nBrake fluids must have certain characteristics and meet certain quality standards for the braking system to work properly.\n\n===Viscosity===\nFor reliable, consistent brake system operation, brake fluid must maintain a constant viscosity under a wide range of temperatures, including extreme cold. This is especially important in systems with an [[anti-lock braking system]] (ABS), [[traction control]], and [[stability control]] (ESP), as these systems often use micro-valves and require very rapid activation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.partinfo.co.uk/articles/63|title=Brake Fluid Exchange and Technology|website=Partinfo.co.uk|accessdate=2018-05-16}}</ref>  DOT 5.1 fluids are specified with low viscosity over a wide range of temperatures, although not all cars fitted with ABS or ESP specify DOT 5.1 brake fluid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trwaftermarket.com/en/passenger-cars-and-lcv/actuation-systems/brake-fluid/|title=Brake Fluid|website=Trwaftermarket.com|accessdate=2018-05-26}}</ref>\nEven more car factory provides or recommends for a faster reaction of the ABS and ESP systems the DOT 4 LV (low viscosity) brake fluids.\nThe specific V100 value of this products 1,50 - 2,00 mm2/sec.\n\n===Boiling point===\nBrake fluid is subjected to very high temperatures, especially in the [[wheel cylinder]]s of [[drum brake]]s and [[disk brake]] calipers. It must have a high boiling point to avoid vaporizing in the lines. This vaporization creates a problem because vapor is highly compressible relative to liquid, and therefore negates the hydraulic transfer of braking force - so the brakes will fail to stop the vehicle.<ref name=epic>{{cite web|url=http://www.epicbleedsolutions.com/blog/dot-brake-fluid-vs-mineral-oil/|title=DOT Brake Fluid vs. Mineral Oil|website=Epicbleedsolutions.com|accessdate=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\nQuality standards refer to a brake fluid's \"dry\" and \"wet\" boiling points. The wet boiling point, which is usually much lower (although above most normal service temperatures), refers to the fluid's boiling point after absorbing a certain amount of moisture. This is several (single digit) percent, varying from formulation to formulation. Glycol-ether (DOT 3, 4, and 5.1) brake fluids are [[Hygroscopy|hygroscopic]] (water absorbing), which means they absorb moisture from the atmosphere under normal humidity levels.  Non-hygroscopic fluids (e.g. [[silicone]]/DOT 5 and mineral oil based formulations), are [[hydrophobic]], and can maintain an acceptable boiling point over the fluid's service life.\n\nSilicone based fluid is more compressible than glycol based fluid, leading to brakes with a ''spongy'' feeling.<ref name=epic/> It can potentially suffer phase separation/water pooling and freezing/boiling in the system over time - the main reason single phase hygroscopic fluids are used.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Characteristics of common braking fluids<ref name=\"DOT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/granule/CFR-2011-title49-vol6/CFR-2011-title49-vol6-sec571-116|title=49 CFR 571.116 - Standard No. 116; Motor vehicle brake fluids.|website=Gpo.gov|accessdate=2018-07-06}}</ref><ref name=epic/>\n|-\n!\n! Dry [[boiling point]]\n! Wet boiling point{{efn|\"Wet\" defined as 3.7% water by volume}}\n! Viscosity limit\n! Primary constituent\n|-\n| DOT 2 || {{convert|190|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|140|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || ? || castor oil/alcohol\n|-\n| DOT 3 || {{convert|205|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|140|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 1500 {{mm2}}/s || [[Glycol ethers|glycol ether]]\n|-\n| DOT 4  || {{convert|230|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|155|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 1800 {{mm2}}/s || glycol ether/[[borate ester]]\n|-\n| [[Hydropneumatic suspension#LHS versus LHM|LHM+]] || {{convert|249|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|249|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 1200 {{mm2}}/s <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viscopedia.com/viscosity-tables/substances/automotive-brake-fluid/|title=Viscosity of Automotive brake fluid \u2013 viscosity table and viscosity chart :: Anton Paar Wiki|website=Anton Paar|accessdate=2018-07-06}}</ref> || mineral oil\n|-\n| DOT 5 || {{convert|260|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|180|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 900 {{mm2}}/s || silicone\n|-\n| DOT 5.1 || {{convert|260|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || {{convert|180|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} || 900 {{mm2}}/s || glycol ether/borate ester\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Corrosion===\nBrake fluids must not corrode the metals used inside components such as calipers, wheel cylinders, master cylinders and ABS control valves. They must also protect against corrosion as moisture enters the system. Additives (corrosion inhibitors) are added to the base fluid to accomplish this. Silicone is less corrosive to paintwork unlike glycol-ether based DOT fluids.<ref name=epic/>\n\nThe advantage of the Citro\u00ebn LHM mineral oil based brake fluid is the absence of corrosion. Seals may wear out at high mileages but otherwise these systems have exceptional longevity. It cannot be used as a substitute without changing seals due to incompatibility with the rubber.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xpowerforums.com/Brake_Fluidsl_FA_Questions.htm|title=AN EXPLANATION OF BRAKE AND CLUTCH FLUIDS|website=Xpowerforums.com|accessdate=2015-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Compressibility===\nBrake fluids must maintain a low level of compressibility, even with varying temperatures to accommodate different environmental conditions. This is important to ensure consistent brake pedal feel. As compressibility increases, more brake pedal travel is necessary for the same amount of brake caliper piston force.\n\n==Service and maintenance==\n\nGlycol-ether (DOT 3, 4, and 5.1) brake fluids are hygroscopic (water absorbing), which means they absorb moisture from the atmosphere under normal humidity levels. Non-hygroscopic fluids (e.g. silicone/DOT 5 and mineral oil based formulations), are hydrophobic, and can maintain an acceptable boiling point over the fluid's service life. Ideally, silicone fluid should be used only to fill non-ABS systems that have not been previously filled with glycol based fluid. Any system that has used glycol-based fluid (DOT 3/4/5.1) will contain moisture; glycol fluid disperses the moisture throughout the system and contains corrosion inhibitors. Silicone fluid does not allow moisture to enter the system, but does not disperse any that is already there, either. A system filled from dry with silicone fluid does not require the fluid to be changed at intervals, only when the system has been disturbed for a component repair or renewal. The United States armed forces have standardised on silicone brake fluid since the 1990s. Silicone fluid is used extensively in cold climates, particularly in Russia and Finland.\n\nBrake fluids with different DOT ratings can not always be mixed. DOT 5 should not be mixed with any of the others as mixing of glycol with silicone fluid may cause corrosion because of trapped moisture.  DOT 2 should not be mixed with any of the others.  DOT 3, DOT 4, and DOT 5.1 are all based on glycol esters and can be mixed, although it is preferable to completely replace existing fluids with fresh to obtain the specified performance.\n\nBrake fluid is toxic<ref name=\"toxicity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.online.petro-canada.ca/datasheets/en_CA/w449.pdf|title=MSDS for DOT 3 brake fluid|website=Online.petro-canada.ca|accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref> and can damage painted surfaces.<ref name=\"Paint damage by Brake Fluid\">{{cite web|url=http://www.totalmotorcycle.com/maintenance/generaltips.htm|title=General Tips|publisher=Total Motorcycle|accessdate=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\n==Components==\n=== Castor oil-based (pre-DOT, DOT 2) ===\n* [[Castor oil]]\n* [[Alcohol]], usually [[butanol]] (red / crimson fluid) or [[ethanol]] (yellow fluid) (methanol)\n\n===Glycol-based (DOT 3, 4, 5.1)===\n* [[Alkyl ester]]\n* [[Aliphatic]] [[amine]]\n* [[Diethylene glycol]]\n* [[Diethylene glycol monoethyl ether]]\n* [[Diethylene glycol monomethyl ether]]\n* [[Dimethyl dipropylene glycol]]\n* [[Polyethylene glycol monobutyl ether]]\n* [[Polyethylene glycol monomethyl ether]]\n* [[Polyethylene oxide]]\n* [[Triethylene glycol monobutyl ether]]\n* [[Triethylene glycol monoethyl ether]]\n* [[Triethylene glycol monomethyl ether]]\n\n===Silicone-based (DOT 5)===\n* [[Dioctyl sebacate|Di-2-ethylhexyl sebacate]]\n* [[Dimethyl polysiloxane]]\n* [[Tributyl phosphate]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hydropneumatic]]\n* [[Pascal's law]]\n*[[Brake fluid pressure sensor]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070304074607/http://www.carcare.org/Brakes/brake_fluid.shtml Car care council]\n* [http://auto.howstuffworks.com/auto-parts/brakes/brake-parts/types-of-brake-fluid.htm ''How Stuff Works: What are the different types of brake fluid?'']\n* [http://www.stoptech.com/tech_info/wp_brakefluid_1a.shtml StopTech: Brake Fluid 1A]\n\n{{Motor fuel}}\n{{Powertrain}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brake Fluid}}\n[[Category:Vehicle braking technologies]]\n[[Category:Automotive chemicals]]\n[[Category:Hydraulic fluids]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brake_fluid"}
{"title_page": "Brain Fuck Scheduler", "text_new": "{{about|the task scheduler|the similarly named but unrelated programming language|Brainfuck}}\n{{Update|date=November 2016|talksection=MuQSS}}\n{{Infobox software\n| logo                   = \n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = \n| collapsible            = \n| developer              = [[Con Kolivas]]\n| discontinued           = Yes\n| latest_release_version = 0.512\n| latest_release_date    = {{Start date and age|2016|10|03}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ck-hack.blogspot.co.uk/2016/10/bfs-version-0512-linux-48-ck1-muqss-for.html|title=-ck hacking: BFS version 0.512, linux-4.8-ck1, MuQSS for linux-4.8 |website=ck-hack.blogspot.com |date=2016-10-03 |accessdate=2016-11-10}}</ref>\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = \n| programming language   = [[C (programming language)|C]]\n| operating_system       = [[Linux]]\n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = \n<!--| status                 = Discontinued<ref name = \"bfsretired\" />-->\n| genre                  = \n| license                = [[GNU GPL]]\n| website                = {{URL|http://kernel.kolivas.org/}}\n}}\n[[File:Simplified_Structure_of_the_Linux_Kernel.svg|thumb|upright=1.7|The location of [[process scheduler]]s in a simplified structure of the [[Linux kernel]]]]\nThe '''Brain Fuck Scheduler''' ('''BFS''') is a [[process scheduler]] designed for the [[Linux kernel]] in August 2009 as an alternative to the [[Completely Fair Scheduler]] (CFS) and the [[O(1) scheduler]].<ref name=\"Linux Pro Magazine on BFS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linuxpromagazine.com/Online/News/Con-Kolivas-Introduces-New-BFS-Scheduler |title=Con Kolivas Introduces New BFS Scheduler \u00bb Linux Magazine |publisher=Linuxpromagazine.com |date=2009-09-02 |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> BFS was created by veteran kernel programmer [[Con Kolivas]].<ref name=\"bfsfaq\">{{cite web|url=http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/bfs/bfs-faq.txt |title=FAQs about BFS v0.330 |publisher=Ck.kolivas.org |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n\nThe objective of BFS, compared to other schedulers, is to provide a scheduler with a simpler algorithm, that does not require adjustment of heuristics or tuning parameters to tailor performance to a specific type of computation workload. Kolivas asserted that these tunable parameters were difficult for the average user to understand, especially in terms of interactions of multiple parameters with each other, and claimed that the use of such tuning parameters could often result in improved performance in a specific targeted type of computation, at the cost of worse performance in the general case.<ref name=\"bfsfaq\"/> BFS has been reported to improve responsiveness on Linux desktop computers with fewer than 16 [[CPU core|cores]].<ref name=\"shedulers compared\" />\n\nShortly following its introduction, the new scheduler made headlines within the Linux community, appearing on ''[[Slashdot]]'', with reviews in ''[[Linux Magazine (USA)|Linux Magazine]]'' and ''[[Linux Magazine|Linux Pro Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"Linux Pro Magazine on BFS\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slashdot.org/story/09/09/06/0433209/Con-Kolivas-Returns-With-a-Slashdo |title=Con Kolivas Returns, With a Desktop-Oriented Linux Scheduler |publisher=Slashdot |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linux-magazine.com/Online/News/Ingo-Molnar-Tests-New-BF-Scheduler |title=Ingo Molnar Tests New BF Scheduler |publisher=Linux Magazine |date=2009-09-08 |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> Although there have been varied reviews of improved performance and responsiveness, Con Kolivas did not intend for BFS to be integrated into the mainline kernel.<ref name=\"bfsfaq\" />\n\n==Theoretical design and efficiency==\n\nBFS uses a [[doubly linked list]] data structure,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\">{{cite web|url=http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/4.0/4.0/4.0-ck1/patches/4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch |title=4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch |publisher=Con Kolivas |date=2015-04-16 |accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref> but the data structure is treated like a [[FIFO (computing and electronics)|queue]].  Task insertion is {{var|O}}(1).<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 119-120}}  Task search for next task to execute is {{var|O}}({{var|n}}) worst case.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 209}}  It uses a single global [[run queue]] which all CPUs use.  Tasks with higher scheduling priorities get executed first.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4146\u20134161}}  Tasks are ordered (or distributed) and chosen based on the virtual deadline formula in all policies except for the realtime and Isochronous priority classes.\n\nThe execution behavior is still a weighted variation of the [[Round-robin scheduling|Round-Robin Scheduler]] especially when tasks have the same priority below the Isochronous policy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1193-1195, 334-335}}  The user tuneable round robin interval ([[time slice]]) is 6 milliseconds by default which was chosen as the minimal [[jitter]] just below detectable by humans.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 306}}  Kolivas claimed that anything below the 6 ms was pointless and anything above 300 ms for the round robin timeslice is fruitless in terms of throughput.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 314-320}}  This important tuneable can tailor the round robin scheduler as a trade off between throughput and latency.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 229\u2013320}}  All tasks get the same time slice with the exception of realtime FIFO which is assumed to have infinite time slice.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1646, 1212\u20131218, 4062, 3910}}\n\nKolivas explained the reason why he choose to go with the doubly linked list mono-runqueue than the multi-runqueue (round robin<ref name=\"lwn-224865\" />{{rp|par. 3}}) priority array<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726235345/http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/staircase-deadline/sched-rsdl-0.26.patch |title=sched-rsdl-0.26.patch |publisher=Con Kolivas |date= |accessdate=2019-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"lwn-224865\">{{cite web|url=https://lwn.net/Articles/224865/ |publisher=corbet |title=The Rotating Staircase Deadline Scheduler |date=2007-03-06 |accessdate=2019-01-30}}</ref> per CPU that was used in his RDSL scheduler was to put to ease fairness among the multiple CPU scenario and remove complexity that each runqueue in a multi-runqueue scenario had to maintain its own latencies and <nowiki>[task]</nowiki> fairness.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 81-92}}  He claimed that deterministic latencies was guaranteed with BFS in his later iteration of MuQSS.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 471\u2013472}}  He also recognized possible lock contention problem (related to the altering, removal, creation of task node data)<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 126\u2013144}} with increasing CPUs and the overhead of {{var|O}}(log {{var|n}}) next task for execution lookup.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 472\u2013478}}  MuQSS tried to resolve those problems.\n\n===Virtual deadline===\n\nThe virtual deadline formula is a future deadline time that is the scaled round robin timeslice based on the nice level offset by the current time (in niffy units or nanosecond [[jiffies]] aka an internal kernel time counter).<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4023, 4063}}  The virtual deadline only suggests the order but doesn't guarantee that a task will run exactly on the future scheduled niffy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 161-163}}\n\nFirst a prio ratios lookup table is created.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 8042-8044}}  It is based on a recursive sequence.  It increases 10% each nice level.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 161}}  It follows a parabolic pattern if graphed, and the niced tasks are distributed as a moving squared function from 0 to 39 (corresponding from highest to lowest nice priority) as the domain and 128 to 5089 as the range.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 177-179, 120, 184-185}}  The moving part comes from the <math>t</math> variable in the virtual deadline formula that Kolivas hinted.\n\n<math>\ng_0 = 128\n</math>\n\n<math>\ng_i = INT( g_{i-1}*11/10 )\n</math>\n\n{| cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible autocollapse\"\n! Index \n! Numerator\n|-  \n| 0 || 128 \n|-  \n| 1 || 140 \n|-  \n| 2 || 154 \n|-  \n| 3 || 169 \n|-  \n| 4 || 185 \n|-  \n| 5 || 203 \n|-  \n| 6 || 223 \n|-  \n| 7 || 245 \n|-  \n| 8 || 269 \n|-  \n| 9 || 295 \n|-  \n| 10 || 324 \n|-  \n| 11 || 356 \n|-  \n| 12 || 391 \n|-  \n| 13 || 430 \n|-  \n| 14 || 473 \n|-  \n| 15 || 520 \n|-  \n| 16 || 572 \n|-  \n| 17 || 629 \n|-  \n| 18 || 691 \n|-  \n| 19 || 760 \n|-  \n| 20 || 836 \n|-  \n| 21 || 919 \n|-  \n| 22 || 1010 \n|-  \n| 23 || 1111 \n|-  \n| 24 || 1222 \n|-  \n| 25 || 1344 \n|-  \n| 26 || 1478 \n|-  \n| 27 || 1625 \n|-  \n| 28 || 1787 \n|-  \n| 29 || 1965 \n|-  \n| 30 || 2161 \n|-  \n| 31 || 2377 \n|-  \n| 32 || 2614 \n|-  \n| 33 || 2875 \n|-  \n| 34 || 3162 \n|-  \n| 35 || 3478 \n|-  \n| 36 || 3825 \n|-  \n| 37 || 4207 \n|-  \n| 38 || 4627 \n|-  \n| 39 || 5089\n|}\n\nThe task's [[nice (Unix)|nice]]-to-index mapping function <math>f(n)</math> is mapped from nice \u221220\u202619 to index 0\u202639 to be used as the input to the prio ratio lookup table.  This mapping function is the TASK_USER_PRIO() macro in sched.h in the kernel header.  The internal kernel implementation slightly differs with range between 100\u2013140 static priority but users will see it as \u221220\u202619 nice.\n\n{| cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible autocollapse\"\n! Nice\n! Index\n|-\n| \u221220 || 0 \n|-\n| \u221219 || 1 \n|-\n| \u221218 || 2 \n|-\n| \u221217 || 3 \n|-\n| \u221216 || 4 \n|-\n| \u221215 || 5 \n|-\n| \u221214 || 6 \n|-\n| \u221213 || 7 \n|-\n| \u221212 || 8 \n|-\n| \u221211 || 9 \n|-\n| \u221210 || 10 \n|-\n| \u22129 || 11 \n|-\n| \u22128 || 12 \n|-\n| \u22127 || 13 \n|-\n| \u22126 || 14 \n|-\n| \u22125 || 15 \n|-\n| \u22124 || 16 \n|-\n| \u22123 || 17 \n|-\n| \u22122 || 18 \n|-\n| \u22121 || 19 \n|-\n| 0 || 20 \n|-\n| 1 || 21 \n|-\n| 2 || 22 \n|-\n| 3 || 23 \n|-\n| 4 || 24 \n|-\n| 5 || 25 \n|-\n| 6 || 26 \n|-\n| 7 || 27 \n|-\n| 8 || 28 \n|-\n| 9 || 29 \n|-\n| 10 || 30 \n|-\n| 11 || 31 \n|-\n| 12 || 32 \n|-\n| 13 || 33 \n|-\n| 14 || 34 \n|-\n| 15 || 35 \n|-\n| 16 || 36 \n|-\n| 17 || 37 \n|-\n| 18 || 38 \n|-\n| 19 || 39\n|}\n\nThe virtual deadline is based on this exact formula:<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4063, 4036, 4033, 1180}}\n\n<math>\nT = 6\n</math>\n\n<math>\nN = 1<<20\n</math>\n\n<math>\nd(n,t) = t + g(f(n)) * T * (N/128)\n</math>\n\n\nAlternatively,\n\n<math>\nd(n,t) = \\frac{g(f(n))}{128} * T * N + t\n</math>\n\n\nwhere <math>d(n,t)</math> is the virtual deadline in u64 integer nanoseconds as a function of nice <math>n</math> and <math>t</math> which is the current time in niffies (as in nanosecond jiffies), <math>g(i)</math> is the prio ratio table lookup as a function of index, <math>f(n)</math> is the task's nice-to-index mapping function, <math>T</math> is the round robin timeslice in milliseconds, <math>N</math> is a constant of 1 millisecond in terms of nanoseconds as a latency reducing approximation of the conversion factor of <math>\\frac{10^9 ns}{10^3 ms}</math> but Kolivas uses a base 2 constant <math>N</math> with approximately that scale.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1173\u20131174}}  Smaller values of <math>d</math> mean that the virtual deadline is earlier corresponding to negative nice values.  Larger values of <math>d</math> indicate the virtual deadline is pushed back later corresponding to positive nice values.  It uses this formula whenever the timeslice expires.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 5087}}\n\n128 in base 2 corresponds to 100 in base 10 and possibly a \"pseudo 100.\"<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 3415}}  115 in base 2 corresponds to 90 in base 10.  Kolivas uses 128 for \"fast [[Bitwise_operation#Bit_shifts|shifts]],\"<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 3846, 1648, 3525}} as in division is right shift base 2.\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> The alternative formula is presented for ease of understanding.  All math is done in integer math so precision loss would be great.  It is possibly why Kolivas deferred the division by 128 to one of the largest numbers as a multiple of 128 resulting in no remainder.\n\n{| cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible autocollapse\" \n! Nice\n! Virtual Deadline in timeslices relative to <math>t</math>\n! Virtual Deadline in exact seconds relative to <math>t</math>\n|-\n| \u221220 || 1.0 || 0.006\n|-\n| \u221219 || 1.09 || 0.006562\n|-\n| \u221218 || 1.2 || 0.007219\n|-\n| \u221217 || 1.3 || 0.007922\n|-\n| \u221216 || 1.4 || 0.008672\n|-\n| \u221215 || 1.5 || 0.009516\n|-\n| \u221214 || 1.7 || 0.010453\n|-\n| \u221213 || 1.9 || 0.011484\n|-\n| \u221212 || 2.1 || 0.012609\n|-\n| \u221211 || 2.3 || 0.013828\n|-\n| \u221210 || 2.5 || 0.015187\n|-\n| \u22129 || 2.7 || 0.016688\n|-\n| \u22128 || 3.0 || 0.018328\n|-\n| \u22127 || 3.3 || 0.020156\n|-\n| \u22126 || 3.6 || 0.022172\n|-\n| \u22125 || 4.0 || 0.024375\n|-\n| \u22124 || 4.4 || 0.026812\n|-\n| \u22123 || 4.9 || 0.029484\n|-\n| \u22122 || 5.3 || 0.032391\n|-\n| \u22121 || 5.9 || 0.035625\n|-\n| 0 || 6.5 || 0.039188\n|-\n| 1 || 7.1 || 0.043078\n|-\n| 2 || 7.8 || 0.047344\n|-\n| 3 || 8.6 || 0.052078\n|-\n| 4 || 9.5 || 0.057281\n|-\n| 5 || 10.5 || 0.063000\n|-\n| 6 || 11.5 || 0.069281\n|-\n| 7 || 12.6 || 0.076172\n|-\n| 8 || 13.9 || 0.083766\n|-\n| 9 || 15.3 || 0.092109\n|-\n| 10 || 16.8 || 0.101297\n|-\n| 11 || 18.5 || 0.111422\n|-\n| 12 || 20.4 || 0.122531\n|-\n| 13 || 22.4 || 0.134766\n|-\n| 14 || 24.7 || 0.148219\n|-\n| 15 || 27.1 || 0.163031\n|-\n| 16 || 29.8 || 0.179297\n|-\n| 17 || 32.8 || 0.197203\n|-\n| 18 || 36.1 || 0.216891\n|-\n| 19 || 39.7 || 0.238547\n|}\n\n===Scheduling policies===\n\nBFS uses scheduling policies to determine how much of the CPU tasks may use.  BFS uses 4 scheduling tiers (called scheduling policies or scheduling classes) ordered from best to worst which determines how tasks are selected<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4146-4161}} with the ones on top being executed first.\n\nEach task has a special value called a prio.  In the v0.462 edition (used in the -ck 4.0 kernel patchset), there are total of 103 \"priority queues\" (aka prio) or allowed values that it can take.  No actual special data structure was used as the priority queue but only the doubly linked list runqueue itself.  The lower prio value means it is more important and gets executed first.\n\n====Realtime policy====\n\nThe realtime policy was designed for [[Real-time computing|realtime]] tasks.  This policy implies that the running tasks cannot be interrupted (i.e. preempted) by the lower prio-ed task or lower priority policy tiers.  Priority classes considered under the realtime policy by the scheduler are those marked SCHED_RR and SCHED_FIFO.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 351, 1150}}  The scheduler treats realtime round robin (SCHED_RR) and realtime FIFO (SCHED_FIFO) differently.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 3881-3934}}\n\nThe design laid out first 100 static priority queues.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 189}} \n\nThe task that will get chosen for execution is based on task availability of the lowest value of prio of the 100 queues and FIFO scheduling.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4146\u20134161}}\n\nOn [[Fork (system call)|forks]], the process priority will be demoted to normal policy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2708}}\n\nOn unprivileged use (i.e. non-root user) of sched_setscheduler called with a request for realtime policy class, the scheduler will demote the task to Isochronous policy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 350\u2013359, 5023\u20135025}}\n\n====Isochronous policy====\n\nThe Isochronous policy was designed for near realtime performance for non-[[superuser|root]] users.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 325}}\n\nThe design laid out 1 priority queue that by default ran as pseudo-realtime tasks, but can be tuned as a degree of realtime.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1201, 346\u2013348}}  .\n\nThe behavior of the policy can allow a task can be demoted to normal policy<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 336}} when it exceeds a tuneable resource handling percentage (70% by default<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 343, 432}}) of 5 seconds scaled to the number of online CPUs and the timer resolution plus 1 tick.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 343, 3844\u20133859, 1167, 338}}<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1678, 4770\u20134783, 734}}  The formula was altered in MuQSS due to the multi-runqueue design.  The exact formulas are:\n\n<math>\nT_{BFS} = ((5*F*n)+1)*R\n</math>\n<br />\n<math>\nT_{MuQSS} = (5*F)*R\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>T</math> is the total number of isochronous ticks, <math>F</math> is the timer frequency, <math>n</math> is the number of online CPUs, <math>R</math> is the tuneable resource handling percentage not in decimal but as a whole number.  The timer frequency is set to 250 by default and editable in the kernel, but usually tuned to 100 Hz for servers and 1000 Hz for interactive desktops.  250 is the balanced value.  Setting <math>R</math> to 100 made tasks behave as realtime and 0 made it not pseudo-realtime and anything in the middle was pseudo-realtime.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 346\u2013348}}\n\nThe task that had an earliest virtual deadline was chosen for execution, but when multiple Isochronous tasks are in existence, they schedule as round robin allowing tasks to run the tuneable round robin value (with 6 ms as the default) one after another in a fair equal chance without considering the nice level.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 334}}\n\nThis behavior of the Isochronous policy is unique to only BFS and MuQSS and may not be implemented in other CPU schedulers.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 324, 8484\u20138485}}<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1287\u20131288}}\n\n====Normal policy====\n\nThe normal policy was designed for regular use and is the default policy.  Newly created tasks are typically marked normal.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 502}} \n\nThe design laid out one priority queue and tasks are chosen to be executed first based on earliest virtual deadline.\n\n====Idle priority policy====\n\nThe idle priority was designed for background processes such as [[distributed program]]s and [[transcoders]] so that foreground processes or those above this scheduling policy can run uninterrupted.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 363\u2013368}}\n\nThe design laid out 1 priority queue and tasks can be [[Aging (scheduling)|promoted]] to normal policy automatically to prevent [[Starvation (computer science)|indefinite resource hold]].<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 368}}\n\nThe next executed task with Idle priority with others residing in the same priority policy is selected by the earliest virtual deadline.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4160\u20134161}}\n\n===Preemption===\n\n[[Preemption (computing)|Preemption]] can occur when a newly ready task with a higher priority policy (i.e. higher prio) has an earlier virtual deadline than the currently running task - which will be descheduled and put at the back of the queue.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 169\u2013175}}  Descheduled means that its virtual deadline is updated.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 165\u2013166}}  The task's time gets refilled to max round robin quantum when it has used up all its time.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4057\u20134062, 5856}}  If the scheduler found the task at the higher prio with the earliest virtual deadline, it will execute in place of the less important currently running task only if all logical CPUs (including hyperthreaded cores / SMT threads) are busy.  The scheduler will delay preemption as long as possible if there are unused logical CPUs.\n\nIf a task is marked idle priority policy, it cannot preempt at all even other idle policy marked tasks but rather use [[cooperative multitasking]].<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2341\u20132344}}\n\n===Task placement, multiple cores===\n\nWhen the scheduler discovers a waking task, it will need to determine which logical CPU to run the wakening task on the non-unicore system.  The scheduler favors most the idle [[Hyper-threading|hyperthreaded]] cores (or idle [[Simultaneous multithreading|SMT]] threads) first on the same CPU that the task executed on,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 261}} then the other idle core of a multicore CPU,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 262}} then the other CPUs on the same NUMA node,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 267, 263\u2013266, 255\u2013258}} then all busy hyperthreaded cores / SMT threads / logical CPUs to be preempted on the same [[Non-uniform memory access|NUMA]] node,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 265\u2013267}} then the other (remote) NUMA node<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 268\u2013270}} and is ranked on a preference list.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 255\u2013274}}  This special scan exists to minimize latency overhead resulting of migrating the task.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 245, 268\u2013272}}\n\nThe preemption order is similar to the above paragraph.  The preemption order is hyperthreaded core / SMT units on the same multicore first, then the other core in the multicore, then the other CPU on the same NUMA node.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 265-267}}  When it goes scanning for a task to preempt in the other remote NUMA node, the preemption is just any busy threads with lower to equal prio or later virtual deadline assuming that all logical CPUs (including hyperthreaded core / SMT threads) in the machine are all busy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 270}}  The scheduler will have to scan for a suitable task with a lower or maybe equal priority policy task (with a later virtual deadline if necessary) to preempt and avoid logical CPUs with a task with a higher priority policy which it cannot preempt.  Local preemption has a higher rank than scanning for a remote idle NUMA unit.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 265\u2013269}}\n\nWhen a task is involuntary preempted at the time the CPU is slowed down as a result of kernel mediated [[Dynamic frequency scaling|CPU frequency scaling]] (aka CPU frequency governor), the task is specially marked \"sticky\" except those marked as realtime policy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2085}}  Marked sticky indicates that the task still has unused time and the task is restricted executing to the same CPU.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 233\u2013243}}  The task will be marked sticky whenever the CPU scaling governor has scaled the CPU at a slower speed.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2082\u20132107, 8840\u20138848}}  The idled stickied task will return to either executing at full Ghz speed by chance or to be rescheduled to execute on the best idle CPU that is not the same CPU that the task ran on.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2082\u20132086, 239\u2013242, 2068\u20132079}}  It is not desirable to migrate the task to other places but make it idle instead because of increased latency brought about of overhead to migrating the task to another CPU or NUMA node.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 228, 245}}  This sticky feature was removed in the last iteration of BFS (v0.512) corresponding to Kolivas' patchset 4.8-ck1 and did not exist in MuQSS.\n\n==schedtool==\n\nA privileged user can change the priority policy of a process with the schedtool program<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 326, 373}} or it is done by a program itself.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 336}}  The priority class can be manipulated at the code level with a [[syscall]] like sched_setscheduler only available to root,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linuxjournal.com/article/3910 |title=The Linux Scheduler |publisher=Moshe Bar |date=2000-04-01 |accessdate=2019-01-29 }}</ref> which schedtool uses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/freequaos/schedtool/blob/c7bf73dc92633713268c6b5393170fa3cfe369ec/schedtool.c#L431 |title=schedtool.c |accessdate=2019-01-30 |date=2017-07-17 |publisher=freek}}</ref>\n\n==Benchmarks==\nIn a contemporary study,<ref name=\"shedulers compared\">{{cite web|url=http://repo-ck.com/bench/cpu_schedulers_compared.pdf |title=CPU Schedulers Compared |publisher=Repo-ck.com |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> the author compared the BFS to the CFS using the Linux kernel v3.6.2 and several performance-based endpoints. The purpose of this study was to evaluate the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) in the [[Vanilla (software)|vanilla]] Linux kernel and the BFS in the corresponding kernel patched with the ck1 patchset. Seven different machines were used to see if differences exist and, to what degree they scale using performance based metrics. Number of logical CPUs ranged from 1 to 16. These end-points were never factors in the primary design goals of the BFS. The results were encouraging.\n\nKernels patched with the ck1 patch set including the BFS outperformed the vanilla kernel using the CFS at nearly all the performance-based benchmarks tested.<ref name=\"shedulers compared\">{{cite web|url=http://repo-ck.com/bench/cpu_schedulers_compared.pdf |title=CPU Schedulers Compared |publisher=Repo-ck.com |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> Further study with a larger test set could be conducted, but based on the small test set of 7 PCs evaluated, these increases in process queuing, efficiency/speed are, on the whole, independent of CPU type (mono, dual, quad, hyperthreaded, etc.), CPU architecture (32-bit and 64-bit) and of CPU multiplicity (mono or dual socket).\n\nMoreover, on several \"modern\" CPUs, such as the Intel [[Core 2 Duo]] and [[Core i7]], that represent common workstations and laptops, BFS consistently outperformed the CFS in the vanilla kernel at all benchmarks. Efficiency and speed gains were small to moderate.\n\n==Adoption==\nBFS is the default scheduler for the following desktop Linux distributions:\n\n* [[NimbleX]] and [[Sabayon Linux]] 7<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ostatic.com/blog/sabayon-7-brings-linux-heaven |title=Sabayon 7 Brings Linux Heaven |publisher=Ostatic.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n* [[PCLinuxOS]] 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pclinuxos.com/?p=579 |title=2010 Edition is now available for download. |publisher=PCLinuxOS |date=2013-10-22 |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n* [[Zenwalk]] 6.4<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zenwalk.org/modules/news/article.php?storyid=107 |title=Zenwalk 6.4 is ready ! - Releases - News |publisher=Zenwalk.org |accessdate=2013-10-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023055842/http://www.zenwalk.org/modules/news/article.php?storyid=107 |archivedate=2013-10-23 }}</ref>\n*[[GalliumOS]] 2.1<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.galliumos.org/About_GalliumOS|title=About GalliumOS - GalliumOS Wiki|website=wiki.galliumos.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-08}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, BFS has been added to an experimental branch of [[Google]]'s [[Android (operating system)|Android]] development repository.<ref>[http://android.git.kernel.org/?p=kernel/experimental.git;a=shortlog;h=refs/heads/android-2.6.29-bfs]\n {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922234416/http://android.git.kernel.org/?p=kernel%2Fexperimental.git%3Ba%3Dshortlog%3Bh%3Drefs%2Fheads%2Fandroid-2.6.29-bfs|date=September 22, 2009}}</ref> It was not included in the [[Android version history#Android 2.2\u20132.2.3 Froyo (API level 8)|Froyo release]] after [[blind testing]] did not show an improved user experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lwn.net/Articles/389230/ |title=CyanogenMod 5 for the G1/ADP1 |publisher=Lwn.net |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==MuQSS==\nBFS has been retired in favour of '''MuQSS''', known formally as the '''Multiple Queue Skiplist Scheduler''', a rewritten implementation of the same concept.<ref name=\"bfsretired\">{{cite web|url=https://ck-hack.blogspot.co.uk/2016/10/linux-48-ck2-muqss-version-0114.html|title=ck-hacking: linux-4.8-ck2, MuQSS version 0.114 |website=ck-hack.blogspot.com |date=2016-10-21 |accessdate=2016-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"phoronix-MuQSS\">https://www.phoronix.com/scan.php?page=news_item&px=MuQSS-First-Major-Release</ref>\n\n===Theoretical design and efficiency===\n\nMuQSS uses a bidirectional static arrayed 8 level [[skip list]] and tasks are ordered by static priority <nowiki>[queues]</nowiki> (referring to the scheduling policy) and a virtual deadline.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\">{{cite web|url=http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/4.0/4.18/4.18-ck1/patches/0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch|title=0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch |publisher=Con Kolivas |date=2018-08-27 |accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref>{{rp|ln 519, 525, 537, 588, 608}}  8 was chosen to fit the array in the cacheline.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 523}}  Doubly linked data structure design was chosen to speed up task removal.  Removing a task takes only {{var|O}}(1) with a doubly skip list versus the original design by [[William_Pugh_(computer_scientist)|William Pugh]] which takes {{var|O}}({{var|n}}) worst case.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 458}}\n\nTask insertion is {{var|O}}(log {{var|n}}).<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 458}}  The next task for execution lookup is {{var|O}}({{var|k}}), where {{var|k}} is the number of CPUs.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 589\u2013590, 603, 5125}}  The next task for execution is {{var|O}}(1) per runqueue,<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 5124}} but the scheduler examines every other runqueues to maintain task fairness among CPUs, for latency or balancing (to maximize CPU usage and cache coherency on the same NUMA node over those that access across NUMA nodes), so ultimately {{var|O}}({{var|k}}).<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 591\u2013593, 497\u2013501, 633\u2013656}}  The max number of tasks it can handle are 64k tasks per runqueue per CPU.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 521}}  It uses multiple task runqueues in some configurations one runqueue per CPU, whereas its predecessor BFS only used one task runqueue for all CPUs.\n\nTasks are ordered as a gradient in the skip list in a way that realtime policy priority comes first and idle policy priority comes last.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2356-2358}}  Normal and idle priority policy still get sorted by virtual deadline which uses [[Nice (Unix)|nice]] values.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2353}}  Realtime and Isochronous policy tasks are run in [[FIFO (computing and electronics)|FIFO]] order ignoring nice values.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2350\u20132351}}  New tasks with same key are placed in FIFO order meaning that newer tasks get placed at the end of the list (i.e. top most node vertically), and tasks at 0th level or at the front-bottom get execution first before those at nearest to the top vertically and those furthest away from the head node.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2351\u20132352, 590}}  The key used for inserted sorting is either the static priority<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2345, 2365, }} or the virtual deadline<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2363}}.\n\nThe user can choose to share runqueues among multicore or have a runqueue per logical CPU.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 947\u20131006}}  The speculation of sharing runqueues design was to reduce latency with a tradeoff of throughput.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 947\u20131006}}\n\nA new behavior introduced by MuQSS was the use of the high resolution timer for below millisecond accuracy when timeslices were used up resulting in rescheduling tasks.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 618-630, 3829\u20133851, 3854-3865, 5316}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software|Linux}}\n* [[Fair-share scheduling]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/bfs/bfs-faq.txt Brain Fuck Scheduler FAQ]\n\n{{Linux kernel}}\n{{Linux}}\n\n[[Category:Free software]]\n[[Category:Linux kernel process schedulers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the task scheduler|the similarly named but unrelated programming language|Brainfuck}}\n{{Update|date=November 2016|talksection=MuQSS}}\n{{Infobox software\n| logo                   = \n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = \n| collapsible            = \n| developer              = [[Con Kolivas]]\n| discontinued           = Yes\n| latest_release_version = 0.512\n| latest_release_date    = {{Start date and age|2016|10|03}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ck-hack.blogspot.co.uk/2016/10/bfs-version-0512-linux-48-ck1-muqss-for.html|title=-ck hacking: BFS version 0.512, linux-4.8-ck1, MuQSS for linux-4.8 |website=ck-hack.blogspot.com |date=2016-10-03 |accessdate=2016-11-10}}</ref>\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = \n| programming language   = [[C (programming language)|C]]\n| operating_system       = [[Linux]]\n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = \n<!--| status                 = Discontinued<ref name = \"bfsretired\" />-->\n| genre                  = \n| license                = [[GNU GPL]]\n| website                = {{URL|http://kernel.kolivas.org/}}\n}}\n[[File:Simplified_Structure_of_the_Linux_Kernel.svg|thumb|upright=1.7|The location of [[process scheduler]]s in a simplified structure of the [[Linux kernel]]]]\nThe '''Brain Fuck Scheduler''' ('''BFS''') is a [[process scheduler]] designed for the [[Linux kernel]] in August 2009 as an alternative to the [[Completely Fair Scheduler]] (CFS) and the [[O(1) scheduler]].<ref name=\"Linux Pro Magazine on BFS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linuxpromagazine.com/Online/News/Con-Kolivas-Introduces-New-BFS-Scheduler |title=Con Kolivas Introduces New BFS Scheduler \u00bb Linux Magazine |publisher=Linuxpromagazine.com |date=2009-09-02 |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> BFS was created by veteran kernel programmer [[Con Kolivas]].<ref name=\"bfsfaq\">{{cite web|url=http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/bfs/bfs-faq.txt |title=FAQs about BFS v0.330 |publisher=Ck.kolivas.org |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n\nThe objective of BFS, compared to other schedulers, is to provide a scheduler with a simpler algorithm, that does not require adjustment of heuristics or tuning parameters to tailor performance to a specific type of computation workload. Kolivas asserted that these tunable parameters were difficult for the average user to understand, especially in terms of interactions of multiple parameters with each other, and claimed that the use of such tuning parameters could often result in improved performance in a specific targeted type of computation, at the cost of worse performance in the general case.<ref name=\"bfsfaq\"/> BFS has been reported to improve responsiveness on Linux desktop computers with fewer than 16 [[CPU core|cores]].<ref name=\"shedulers compared\" />\n\nShortly following its introduction, the new scheduler made headlines within the Linux community, appearing on ''[[Slashdot]]'', with reviews in ''[[Linux Magazine (USA)|Linux Magazine]]'' and ''[[Linux Magazine|Linux Pro Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"Linux Pro Magazine on BFS\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slashdot.org/story/09/09/06/0433209/Con-Kolivas-Returns-With-a-Slashdo |title=Con Kolivas Returns, With a Desktop-Oriented Linux Scheduler |publisher=Slashdot |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linux-magazine.com/Online/News/Ingo-Molnar-Tests-New-BF-Scheduler |title=Ingo Molnar Tests New BF Scheduler |publisher=Linux Magazine |date=2009-09-08 |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> Although there have been varied reviews of improved performance and responsiveness, Con Kolivas did not intend for BFS to be integrated into the mainline kernel.<ref name=\"bfsfaq\" />\n\n==Theoretical design and efficiency==\n\nBFS uses a [[doubly linked list]] data structure,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\">{{cite web|url=http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/4.0/4.0/4.0-ck1/patches/4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch |title=4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch |publisher=Con Kolivas |date=2015-04-16 |accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref> but the data structure is treated like a [[FIFO (computing and electronics)|queue]].  Task insertion is {{var|O}}(1).<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 119-120}}  Task search for next task to execute is {{var|O}}({{var|n}}) worst case.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 209}}  It uses a single global [[run queue]] which all CPUs use.  Tasks with higher scheduling priorities get executed first.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4146\u20134161}}  Tasks are ordered (or distributed) and chosen based on the virtual deadline formula in all policies except for the realtime and Isochronous priority classes.\n\nThe execution behavior is still a weighted variation of the [[Round-robin scheduling|Round-Robin Scheduler]] especially when tasks have the same priority below the Isochronous policy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1193-1195, 334-335}}  The user tuneable round robin interval ([[time slice]]) is 6 milliseconds by default which was chosen as the minimal [[jitter]] just below detectable by humans.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 306}}  Kolivas claimed that anything below the 6 ms was pointless and anything above 300 ms for the round robin timeslice is fruitless in terms of throughput.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 314-320}}  This important tuneable can tailor the round robin scheduler as a trade off between throughput and latency.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 229\u2013320}}  All tasks get the same time slice with the exception of realtime FIFO which is assumed to have infinite time slice.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1646, 1212\u20131218, 4062, 3910}}\n\nKolivas explained the reason why he choose to go with the doubly linked list mono-runqueue than the multi-runqueue (round robin<ref name=\"lwn-224865\" />{{rp|par. 3}}) priority array<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726235345/http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/staircase-deadline/sched-rsdl-0.26.patch |title=sched-rsdl-0.26.patch |publisher=Con Kolivas |date= |accessdate=2019-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"lwn-224865\">{{cite web|url=https://lwn.net/Articles/224865/ |publisher=corbet |title=The Rotating Staircase Deadline Scheduler |date=2007-03-06 |accessdate=2019-01-30}}</ref> per CPU that was used in his RDSL scheduler was to put to ease fairness among the multiple CPU scenario and remove complexity that each runqueue in a multi-runqueue scenario had to maintain its own latencies and <nowiki>[task]</nowiki> fairness.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 81-92}}  He claimed that deterministic latencies was guaranteed with BFS in his later iteration of MuQSS.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 471\u2013472}}  He also recognized possible lock contention problem (related to the altering, removal, creation of task node data)<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 126\u2013144}} with increasing CPUs and the overhead of {{var|O}}(log {{var|n}}) next task for execution lookup.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 472\u2013478}}  MuQSS tried to resolve those problems.\n\n===Virtual deadline===\n\nThe virtual deadline formula is a future deadline time that is the scaled round robin timeslice based on the nice level offset by the current time (in niffy units or nanosecond [[jiffies]] aka an internal kernel time counter).<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4023, 4063}}  The virtual deadline only suggests the order but doesn't guarantee that a task will run exactly on the future scheduled niffy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 161-163}}\n\nFirst a prio ratios lookup table is created.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 8042-8044}}  It is based on a recursive sequence.  It increases 10% each nice level.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 161}}  It follows a parabolic pattern if graphed, and the niced tasks are distributed as a moving squared function from 0 to 39 (corresponding from highest to lowest nice priority) as the domain and 128 to 5089 as the range.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 177-179, 120, 184-185}}  The moving part comes from the <math>t</math> variable in the virtual deadline formula that Kolivas hinted.\n\n<math>\ng_0 = 128\n</math>\n\n<math>\ng_i = INT( g_{i-1}*11/10 )\n</math>\n\n{| cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible autocollapse\"\n! Index \n! Numerator\n|-  \n| 0 || 128 \n|-  \n| 1 || 140 \n|-  \n| 2 || 154 \n|-  \n| 3 || 169 \n|-  \n| 4 || 185 \n|-  \n| 5 || 203 \n|-  \n| 6 || 223 \n|-  \n| 7 || 245 \n|-  \n| 8 || 269 \n|-  \n| 9 || 295 \n|-  \n| 10 || 324 \n|-  \n| 11 || 356 \n|-  \n| 12 || 391 \n|-  \n| 13 || 430 \n|-  \n| 14 || 473 \n|-  \n| 15 || 520 \n|-  \n| 16 || 572 \n|-  \n| 17 || 629 \n|-  \n| 18 || 691 \n|-  \n| 19 || 760 \n|-  \n| 20 || 836 \n|-  \n| 21 || 919 \n|-  \n| 22 || 1010 \n|-  \n| 23 || 1111 \n|-  \n| 24 || 1222 \n|-  \n| 25 || 1344 \n|-  \n| 26 || 1478 \n|-  \n| 27 || 1625 \n|-  \n| 28 || 1787 \n|-  \n| 29 || 1965 \n|-  \n| 30 || 2161 \n|-  \n| 31 || 2377 \n|-  \n| 32 || 2614 \n|-  \n| 33 || 2875 \n|-  \n| 34 || 3162 \n|-  \n| 35 || 3478 \n|-  \n| 36 || 3825 \n|-  \n| 37 || 4207 \n|-  \n| 38 || 4627 \n|-  \n| 39 || 5089\n|}\n\nThe task's [[nice (Unix)|nice]]-to-index mapping function <math>f(n)</math> is mapped from nice \u221220\u202619 to index 0\u202639 to be used as the input to the prio ratio lookup table.  This mapping function is the TASK_USER_PRIO() macro in sched.h in the kernel header.  The internal kernel implementation slightly differs with range between 100\u2013140 static priority but users will see it as \u221220\u202619 nice.\n\n{| cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible autocollapse\"\n! Nice\n! Index\n|-\n| \u221220 || 0 \n|-\n| \u221219 || 1 \n|-\n| \u221218 || 2 \n|-\n| \u221217 || 3 \n|-\n| \u221216 || 4 \n|-\n| \u221215 || 5 \n|-\n| \u221214 || 6 \n|-\n| \u221213 || 7 \n|-\n| \u221212 || 8 \n|-\n| \u221211 || 9 \n|-\n| \u221210 || 10 \n|-\n| \u22129 || 11 \n|-\n| \u22128 || 12 \n|-\n| \u22127 || 13 \n|-\n| \u22126 || 14 \n|-\n| \u22125 || 15 \n|-\n| \u22124 || 16 \n|-\n| \u22123 || 17 \n|-\n| \u22122 || 18 \n|-\n| \u22121 || 19 \n|-\n| 0 || 20 \n|-\n| 1 || 21 \n|-\n| 2 || 22 \n|-\n| 3 || 23 \n|-\n| 4 || 24 \n|-\n| 5 || 25 \n|-\n| 6 || 26 \n|-\n| 7 || 27 \n|-\n| 8 || 28 \n|-\n| 9 || 29 \n|-\n| 10 || 30 \n|-\n| 11 || 31 \n|-\n| 12 || 32 \n|-\n| 13 || 33 \n|-\n| 14 || 34 \n|-\n| 15 || 35 \n|-\n| 16 || 36 \n|-\n| 17 || 37 \n|-\n| 18 || 38 \n|-\n| 19 || 39\n|}\n\nThe virtual deadline is based on this exact formula:<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4063, 4036, 4033, 1180}}\n\n<math>\nT = 6\n</math>\n\n<math>\nN = 1<<20\n</math>\n\n<math>\nd(n,t) = t + g(f(n)) * T * (N/128)\n</math>\n\n\nAlternatively,\n\n<math>\nd(n,t) = \\frac{g(f(n))}{128} * T * N + t\n</math>\n\n\nwhere <math>d(n,t)</math> is the virtual deadline in u64 integer nanoseconds as a function of nice <math>n</math> and <math>t</math> which is the current time in niffies (as in nanosecond jiffies), <math>g(i)</math> is the prio ratio table lookup as a function of index, <math>f(n)</math> is the task's nice-to-index mapping function, <math>T</math> is the round robin timeslice in milliseconds, <math>N</math> is a constant of 1 millisecond in terms of nanoseconds as a latency reducing approximation of the conversion factor of <math>\\frac{10^9 ns}{10^3 ms}</math> but Kolivas uses a base 2 constant <math>N</math> with approximately that scale.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1173\u20131174}}  Smaller values of <math>d</math> mean that the virtual deadline is earlier corresponding to negative nice values.  Larger values of <math>d</math> indicate the virtual deadline is pushed back later corresponding to positive nice values.  It uses this formula whenever the timeslice expires.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 5087}}\n\n128 in base 2 corresponds to 100 in base 10 and possibly a \"pseudo 100.\"<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 3415}}  115 in base 2 corresponds to 90 in base 10.  Kolivas uses 128 for \"fast [[Bitwise_operation#Bit_shifts|shifts]],\"<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 3846, 1648, 3525}} as in division is right shift base 2.\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> The alternative formula is presented for ease of understanding.  All math is done in integer math so precision loss would be great.  It is possibly why Kolivas deferred the division by 128 to one of the largest numbers as a multiple of 128 resulting in no remainder.\n\n{| cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible autocollapse\" \n! Nice\n! Virtual Deadline in timeslices relative to <math>t</math>\n! Virtual Deadline in exact seconds relative to <math>t</math>\n|-\n| \u221220 || 1.0 || 0.006\n|-\n| \u221219 || 1.09 || 0.006562\n|-\n| \u221218 || 1.2 || 0.007219\n|-\n| \u221217 || 1.3 || 0.007922\n|-\n| \u221216 || 1.4 || 0.008672\n|-\n| \u221215 || 1.5 || 0.009516\n|-\n| \u221214 || 1.7 || 0.010453\n|-\n| \u221213 || 1.9 || 0.011484\n|-\n| \u221212 || 2.1 || 0.012609\n|-\n| \u221211 || 2.3 || 0.013828\n|-\n| \u221210 || 2.5 || 0.015187\n|-\n| \u22129 || 2.7 || 0.016688\n|-\n| \u22128 || 3.0 || 0.018328\n|-\n| \u22127 || 3.3 || 0.020156\n|-\n| \u22126 || 3.6 || 0.022172\n|-\n| \u22125 || 4.0 || 0.024375\n|-\n| \u22124 || 4.4 || 0.026812\n|-\n| \u22123 || 4.9 || 0.029484\n|-\n| \u22122 || 5.3 || 0.032391\n|-\n| \u22121 || 5.9 || 0.035625\n|-\n| 0 || 6.5 || 0.039188\n|-\n| 1 || 7.1 || 0.043078\n|-\n| 2 || 7.8 || 0.047344\n|-\n| 3 || 8.6 || 0.052078\n|-\n| 4 || 9.5 || 0.057281\n|-\n| 5 || 10.5 || 0.063000\n|-\n| 6 || 11.5 || 0.069281\n|-\n| 7 || 12.6 || 0.076172\n|-\n| 8 || 13.9 || 0.083766\n|-\n| 9 || 15.3 || 0.092109\n|-\n| 10 || 16.8 || 0.101297\n|-\n| 11 || 18.5 || 0.111422\n|-\n| 12 || 20.4 || 0.122531\n|-\n| 13 || 22.4 || 0.134766\n|-\n| 14 || 24.7 || 0.148219\n|-\n| 15 || 27.1 || 0.163031\n|-\n| 16 || 29.8 || 0.179297\n|-\n| 17 || 32.8 || 0.197203\n|-\n| 18 || 36.1 || 0.216891\n|-\n| 19 || 39.7 || 0.238547\n|}\n\n===Scheduling policies===\n\nBFS uses scheduling policies to determine how much of the CPU tasks may use.  BFS uses 4 scheduling tiers (called scheduling policies or scheduling classes) ordered from best to worst which determines how tasks are selected<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4146-4161}} with the ones on top being executed first.\n\nEach task has a special value called a prio.  In the v0.462 edition (used in the -ck 4.0 kernel patchset), there are total of 103 \"priority queues\" (aka prio) or allowed values that it can take.  No actual special data structure was used as the priority queue but only the doubly linked list runqueue itself.  The lower prio value means it is more important and gets executed first.\n\n====Realtime policy====\n\nThe realtime policy was designed for [[Real-time computing|realtime]] tasks.  This policy implies that the running tasks cannot be interrupted (i.e. preempted) by the lower prio-ed task or lower priority policy tiers.  Priority classes considered under the realtime policy by the scheduler are those marked SCHED_RR and SCHED_FIFO.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 351, 1150}}  The scheduler treats realtime round robin (SCHED_RR) and realtime FIFO (SCHED_FIFO) differently.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 3881-3934}}\n\nThe design laid out first 100 static priority queues.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 189}} \n\nThe task that will get chosen for execution is based on task availability of the lowest value of prio of the 100 queues and FIFO scheduling.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4146\u20134161}}\n\nOn [[Fork (system call)|forks]], the process priority will be demoted to normal policy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2708}}\n\nOn unprivileged use (i.e. non-root user) of sched_setscheduler called with a request for realtime policy class, the scheduler will demote the task to Isochronous policy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 350\u2013359, 5023\u20135025}}\n\n====Isochronous policy====\n\nThe Isochronous policy was designed for near realtime performance for non-[[superuser|root]] users.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 325}}\n\nThe design laid out 1 priority queue that by default ran as pseudo-realtime tasks, but can be tuned as a degree of realtime.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1201, 346\u2013348}}  .\n\nThe behavior of the policy can allow a task can be demoted to normal policy<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 336}} when it exceeds a tuneable resource handling percentage (70% by default<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 343, 432}}) of 5 seconds scaled to the number of online CPUs and the timer resolution plus 1 tick.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 343, 3844\u20133859, 1167, 338}}<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1678, 4770\u20134783, 734}}  The formula was altered in MuQSS due to the multi-runqueue design.  The exact formulas are:\n\n<math>\nT_{BFS} = ((5*F*n)+1)*R\n</math>\n<br />\n<math>\nT_{MuQSS} = (5*F)*R\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>T</math> is the total number of isochronous ticks, <math>F</math> is the timer frequency, <math>n</math> is the number of online CPUs, <math>R</math> is the tuneable resource handling percentage not in decimal but as a whole number.  The timer frequency is set to 250 by default and editable in the kernel, but usually tuned to 100 Hz for servers and 1000 Hz for interactive desktops.  250 is the balanced value.  Setting <math>R</math> to 100 made tasks behave as realtime and 0 made it not pseudo-realtime and anything in the middle was pseudo-realtime.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 346\u2013348}}\n\nThe task that had an earliest virtual deadline was chosen for execution, but when multiple Isochronous tasks are in existence, they schedule as round robin allowing tasks to run the tuneable round robin value (with 6 ms as the default) one after another in a fair equal chance without considering the nice level.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 334}}\n\nThis behavior of the Isochronous policy is unique to only BFS and MuQSS and may not be implemented in other CPU schedulers.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 324, 8484\u20138485}}<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 1287\u20131288}}\n\n====Normal policy====\n\nThe normal policy was designed for regular use and is the default policy.  Newly created tasks are typically marked normal.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 502}} \n\nThe design laid out one priority queue and tasks are chosen to be executed first based on earliest virtual deadline.\n\n====Idle priority policy====\n\nThe idle priority was designed for background processes such as [[distributed program]]s and [[transcoders]] so that foreground processes or those above this scheduling policy can run uninterrupted.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 363\u2013368}}\n\nThe design laid out 1 priority queue and tasks can be [[Aging (scheduling)|promoted]] to normal policy automatically to prevent [[Starvation (computer science)|indefinite resource hold]].<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 368}}\n\nThe next executed task with Idle priority with others residing in the same priority policy is selected by the earliest virtual deadline.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4160\u20134161}}\n\n===Preemption===\n\n[[Preemption (computing)|Preemption]] can occur when a newly ready task with a higher priority policy (i.e. higher prio) has an earlier virtual deadline than the currently running task - which will be descheduled and put at the back of the queue.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 169\u2013175}}  Descheduled means that its virtual deadline is updated.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 165\u2013166}}  The task's time gets refilled to max round robin quantum when it has used up all its time.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 4057\u20134062, 5856}}  If the scheduler found the task at the higher prio with the earliest virtual deadline, it will execute in place of the less important currently running task only if all logical CPUs (including hyperthreaded cores / SMT threads) are busy.  The scheduler will delay preemption as long as possible if there are unused logical CPUs.\n\nIf a task is marked idle priority policy, it cannot preempt at all even other idle policy marked tasks but rather use [[cooperative multitasking]].<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2341\u20132344}}\n\n===Task placement, multiple cores===\n\nWhen the scheduler discovers a waking task, it will need to determine which logical CPU to run the wakening task on the non-unicore system.  The scheduler favors most the idle [[Hyper-threading|hyperthreaded]] cores (or idle [[Simultaneous multithreading|SMT]] threads) first on the same CPU that the task executed on,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 261}} then the other idle core of a multicore CPU,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 262}} then the other CPUs on the same NUMA node,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 267, 263\u2013266, 255\u2013258}} then all busy hyperthreaded cores / SMT threads / logical CPUs to be preempted on the same [[Non-uniform memory access|NUMA]] node,<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 265\u2013267}} then the other (remote) NUMA node<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 268\u2013270}} and is ranked on a preference list.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 255\u2013274}}  This special scan exists to minimize latency overhead resulting of migrating the task.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 245, 268\u2013272}}\n\nThe preemption order is similar to the above paragraph.  The preemption order is hyperthreaded core / SMT units on the same multicore first, then the other core in the multicore, then the other CPU on the same NUMA node.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 265-267}}  When it goes scanning for a task to preempt in the other remote NUMA node, the preemption is just any busy threads with lower to equal prio or later virtual deadline assuming that all logical CPUs (including hyperthreaded core / SMT threads) in the machine are all busy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 270}}  The scheduler will have to scan for a suitable task with a lower or maybe equal priority policy task (with a later virtual deadline if necessary) to preempt and avoid logical CPUs with a task with a higher priority policy which it cannot preempt.  Local preemption has a higher rank than scanning for a remote idle NUMA unit.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 265\u2013269}}\n\nWhen a task is involuntary preempted at the time the CPU is slowed down as a result of kernel mediated [[Dynamic frequency scaling|CPU frequency scaling]] (aka CPU frequency governor), the task is specially marked \"sticky\" except those marked as realtime policy.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2085}}  Marked sticky indicates that the task still has unused time and the task is restricted executing to the same CPU.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 233\u2013243}}  The task will be marked sticky whenever the CPU scaling governor has scaled the CPU at a slower speed.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2082\u20132107, 8840\u20138848}}  The idled stickied task will return to either executing at full Ghz speed by chance or to be rescheduled to execute on the best idle CPU that is not the same CPU that the task ran on.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2082\u20132086, 239\u2013242, 2068\u20132079}}  It is not desirable to migrate the task to other places but make it idle instead because of increased latency brought about of overhead to migrating the task to another CPU or NUMA node.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 228, 245}}  This sticky feature was removed in the last iteration of BFS (v0.512) corresponding to Kolivas' patchset 4.8-ck1 and did not exist in MuQSS.\n\n==schedtool==\n\nA privileged user can change the priority policy of a process with the schedtool program<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 326, 373}} or it is done by a program itself.<ref name=\"4.0-sched-bfs-462.patch\" />{{rp|ln 336}}  The priority class can be manipulated at the code level with a [[syscall]] like sched_setscheduler only available to root,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linuxjournal.com/article/3910 |title=The Linux Scheduler |publisher=Moshe Bar |date=2000-04-01 |accessdate=2019-01-29 }}</ref> which schedtool uses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/freequaos/schedtool/blob/c7bf73dc92633713268c6b5393170fa3cfe369ec/schedtool.c#L431 |title=schedtool.c |accessdate=2019-01-30 |date=2017-07-17 |publisher=freek}}</ref>\n\n==Benchmarks==\nIn a contemporary study,<ref name=\"shedulers compared\">{{cite web|url=http://repo-ck.com/bench/cpu_schedulers_compared.pdf |title=CPU Schedulers Compared |publisher=Repo-ck.com |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> the author compared the BFS to the CFS using the Linux kernel v3.6.2 and several performance-based endpoints. The purpose of this study was to evaluate the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) in the [[Vanilla (software)|vanilla]] Linux kernel and the BFS in the corresponding kernel patched with the ck1 patchset. Seven different machines were used to see if differences exist and, to what degree they scale using performance based metrics. Number of logical CPUs ranged from 1 to 16. These end-points were never factors in the primary design goals of the BFS. The results were encouraging.\n\nKernels patched with the ck1 patch set including the BFS outperformed the vanilla kernel using the CFS at nearly all the performance-based benchmarks tested<ref name=\"shedulers compared\">{{cite web|url=http://repo-ck.com/bench/cpu_schedulers_compared.pdf |title=CPU Schedulers Compared |publisher=Repo-ck.com |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>. Further study with a larger test set could be conducted, but based on the small test set of 7 PCs evaluated, these increases in process queuing, efficiency/speed are, on the whole, independent of CPU type (mono, dual, quad, hyperthreaded, etc.), CPU architecture (32-bit and 64-bit) and of CPU multiplicity (mono or dual socket).\n\nMoreover, on several \"modern\" CPUs, such as the Intel [[Core 2 Duo]] and [[Core i7]], that represent common workstations and laptops, BFS consistently outperformed the CFS in the vanilla kernel at all benchmarks. Efficiency and speed gains were small to moderate.\n\n==Adoption==\nBFS is the default scheduler for the following desktop Linux distributions:\n\n* [[NimbleX]] and [[Sabayon Linux]] 7<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ostatic.com/blog/sabayon-7-brings-linux-heaven |title=Sabayon 7 Brings Linux Heaven |publisher=Ostatic.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n* [[PCLinuxOS]] 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pclinuxos.com/?p=579 |title=2010 Edition is now available for download. |publisher=PCLinuxOS |date=2013-10-22 |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n* [[Zenwalk]] 6.4<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zenwalk.org/modules/news/article.php?storyid=107 |title=Zenwalk 6.4 is ready ! - Releases - News |publisher=Zenwalk.org |accessdate=2013-10-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023055842/http://www.zenwalk.org/modules/news/article.php?storyid=107 |archivedate=2013-10-23 }}</ref>\n*[[GalliumOS]] 2.1<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.galliumos.org/About_GalliumOS|title=About GalliumOS - GalliumOS Wiki|website=wiki.galliumos.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-08}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, BFS has been added to an experimental branch of [[Google]]'s [[Android (operating system)|Android]] development repository.<ref>[http://android.git.kernel.org/?p=kernel/experimental.git;a=shortlog;h=refs/heads/android-2.6.29-bfs]\n {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922234416/http://android.git.kernel.org/?p=kernel%2Fexperimental.git%3Ba%3Dshortlog%3Bh%3Drefs%2Fheads%2Fandroid-2.6.29-bfs|date=September 22, 2009}}</ref> It was not included in the [[Android version history#Android 2.2\u20132.2.3 Froyo (API level 8)|Froyo release]] after [[blind testing]] did not show an improved user experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lwn.net/Articles/389230/ |title=CyanogenMod 5 for the G1/ADP1 |publisher=Lwn.net |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==MuQSS==\nBFS has been retired in favour of '''MuQSS''', known formally as the '''Multiple Queue Skiplist Scheduler''', a rewritten implementation of the same concept.<ref name=\"bfsretired\">{{cite web|url=https://ck-hack.blogspot.co.uk/2016/10/linux-48-ck2-muqss-version-0114.html|title=ck-hacking: linux-4.8-ck2, MuQSS version 0.114 |website=ck-hack.blogspot.com |date=2016-10-21 |accessdate=2016-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"phoronix-MuQSS\">https://www.phoronix.com/scan.php?page=news_item&px=MuQSS-First-Major-Release</ref>\n\n===Theoretical design and efficiency===\n\nMuQSS uses a bidirectional static arrayed 8 level [[skip list]] and tasks are ordered by static priority <nowiki>[queues]</nowiki> (referring to the scheduling policy) and a virtual deadline.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\">{{cite web|url=http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/4.0/4.18/4.18-ck1/patches/0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch|title=0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch |publisher=Con Kolivas |date=2018-08-27 |accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref>{{rp|ln 519, 525, 537, 588, 608}}  8 was chosen to fit the array in the cacheline.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 523}}  Doubly linked data structure design was chosen to speed up task removal.  Removing a task takes only {{var|O}}(1) with a doubly skip list versus the original design by [[William_Pugh_(computer_scientist)|William Pugh]] which takes {{var|O}}({{var|n}}) worst case.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 458}}\n\nTask insertion is {{var|O}}(log {{var|n}}).<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 458}}  The next task for execution lookup is {{var|O}}({{var|k}}), where {{var|k}} is the number of CPUs.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 589\u2013590, 603, 5125}}  The next task for execution is {{var|O}}(1) per runqueue,<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 5124}} but the scheduler examines every other runqueues to maintain task fairness among CPUs, for latency or balancing (to maximize CPU usage and cache coherency on the same NUMA node over those that access across NUMA nodes), so ultimately {{var|O}}({{var|k}}).<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 591\u2013593, 497\u2013501, 633\u2013656}}  The max number of tasks it can handle are 64k tasks per runqueue per CPU.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 521}}  It uses multiple task runqueues in some configurations one runqueue per CPU, whereas its predecessor BFS only used one task runqueue for all CPUs.\n\nTasks are ordered as a gradient in the skip list in a way that realtime policy priority comes first and idle policy priority comes last.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2356-2358}}  Normal and idle priority policy still get sorted by virtual deadline which uses [[Nice (Unix)|nice]] values.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2353}}  Realtime and Isochronous policy tasks are run in [[FIFO (computing and electronics)|FIFO]] order ignoring nice values.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2350\u20132351}}  New tasks with same key are placed in FIFO order meaning that newer tasks get placed at the end of the list (i.e. top most node vertically), and tasks at 0th level or at the front-bottom get execution first before those at nearest to the top vertically and those furthest away from the head node.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2351\u20132352, 590}}  The key used for inserted sorting is either the static priority<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2345, 2365, }} or the virtual deadline<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 2363}}.\n\nThe user can choose to share runqueues among multicore or have a runqueue per logical CPU.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 947\u20131006}}  The speculation of sharing runqueues design was to reduce latency with a tradeoff of throughput.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 947\u20131006}}\n\nA new behavior introduced by MuQSS was the use of the high resolution timer for below millisecond accuracy when timeslices were used up resulting in rescheduling tasks.<ref name=\"0001-MultiQueue-Skiplist-Scheduler-version-v0.173.patch\" />{{rp|ln 618-630, 3829\u20133851, 3854-3865, 5316}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software|Linux}}\n* [[Fair-share scheduling]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ck.kolivas.org/patches/bfs/bfs-faq.txt Brain Fuck Scheduler FAQ]\n\n{{Linux kernel}}\n{{Linux}}\n\n[[Category:Free software]]\n[[Category:Linux kernel process schedulers]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_Fuck_Scheduler"}
{"title_page": "2006 California gubernatorial election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2006 California gubernatorial election\n| country            = California\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = California gubernatorial recall election\n| previous_year      = 2003 (recall)\n| next_election      = 2010 California gubernatorial election\n| next_year          = 2010\n| election_date      = November 7, 2006\n| image1             =  [[File:A. Schwarzenegger.jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1           = '''[[Arnold Schwarzenegger]]'''\n| party1             = Republican Party (United States)\n| color1             = FF3333\n| popular_vote1      = '''4,850,157'''\n| percentage1        = '''55.9%'''\n| image2             = [[File:Phil Angelides FCIC.jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee2           = [[Phil Angelides]]\n| party2             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| color2             = 3333FF\n| popular_vote2      = 3,376,732\n| percentage2        = 38.9%\n| map_image          = California Gubernatorial Election Results by County, 2006.svg\n| map_size           = 200px\n| map_caption        = Election results by county<br/>'''Schwarzenegger''': {{legend0|#ffb2b2|40\u201350%}} {{legend0|#e27f7f|50\u201360%}} {{legend0|#d75d5d|60\u201370%}} {{legend0|#d72f30|70\u201380%}}<br/>'''Angelides''': {{legend0|#a5b0ff|40\u201350%}} {{legend0|#7996e2|50\u201360%}} {{legend0|#6674de|60\u201370%}}\n| title              = Governor\n| before_election    = [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     = [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]]\n| after_party        = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsCA}}\nThe '''2006 California gubernatorial election''' occurred on November 7, 2006. The [[primary election]]s took place on June 6, 2006. The incumbent [[California Republican Party|Republican]] [[Governor of California|Governor]], [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], won re-election for his first and only full term. His main opponent was [[California State Treasurer]] [[Phil Angelides]], the [[California Democratic Party]] nominee. [[Peter Camejo]] was the California [[Green Party of California|Green Party]] nominee, [[Janice Jordan]] was the [[Peace and Freedom Party (United States)|Peace and Freedom Party]] nominee, [[Art Olivier]] was the California [[Libertarian Party of California|Libertarian Party]] nominee, and [[Edward C. Noonan]] was the California [[American Independent Party]] nominee.\n\nUnder the [[California Constitution]], the [[Governor of California|Governor]] serves a four-year term, with a maximum [[term limit|limit]] of two consecutive terms.  [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] was elected during the [[2003 California recall]] and served out the remainder of [[Gray Davis]]'s term; he was eligible to serve until 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/sunday/commentary/la-op-jeffe2jul02,0,1256025,print.story?coll=la-sunday-commentary|title=Think it can\u2019t get any wilder?|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080619092345/http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/sunday/commentary/la-op-jeffe2jul02%2C0%2C1256025%2Cprint.story?coll=la-sunday-commentary|archivedate=June 19, 2008|accessdate=October 8, 2006}}</ref> As of {{CURRENTYEAR}}, this is the most recent election in which a Republican won a Gubernatorial or statewide election in California. \n\nExit polls showed Schwarzenegger won whites (63%-32%) and Asian Americans (62%-37%) and other minorities (53%-38%), while Angelides won African Americans (70%-27%) and Latinos (56%-39%).\n\n==Primary elections (June 6, 2006)==\nBar graph of statewide results<ref>{{cite web |url=http://primary2006.ss.ca.gov/Returns/gov/00.htm |title=CA Secretary of State - Primary Election- Governor of California - Statewide |publisher=Primary2006.ss.ca.gov |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828124126/http://primary2006.ss.ca.gov/Returns/gov/00.htm |archive-date=2008-08-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nResults by county<ref>{{cite web |url=http://primary2006.ss.ca.gov/Returns/gov/00.htm#cty |title=CA Secretary of State - Primary Election- Governor of California - Statewide |publisher=Primary2006.ss.ca.gov |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828124126/http://primary2006.ss.ca.gov/Returns/gov/00.htm#cty |archive-date=2008-08-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nThe period for candidate nominations closed on March 24, 2006.<ref>[http://www.ss.ca.gov/elections/election_2006/status/unofficial_list_of_candidates_32806.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205071252/http://www.ss.ca.gov/elections/election_2006/status/unofficial_list_of_candidates_32806.pdf |date=December 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Democratic===\n\n====Candidates====\n*[[Phil Angelides]] \u2013 [[California State Treasurer]]; former State Democratic Chair and developer\n*[[Barbara Becnel]] \u2013 Executive Director of Neighborhood House of North Richmond; founder of Save [[Stanley Tookie Williams]] campaign\n*Joe Brouilette \u2013 high school teacher\n*Edie Bukewihge \u2013 writer and publisher\n*Jerald Gerst \u2013 physician\n*Vibert Greene \u2013 engineer\n*Frank Macaluso \u2013 medical doctor\n*Michael Strimling \u2013 attorney\n*[[Steve Westly]] \u2013 [[California State Controller]]; former Internet executive\n\nThe two front-runners for the Democratic nomination were Angelides and [[California State Controller]] [[Steve Westly]]. A pre-election poll had Westly leading Angelides by six percentage points.<ref>http://www.ppic.org/content/pubs/survey/S_406MBS.pdf</ref> The Field Poll conducted on April 17, 2006 showed that both Democratic candidates had low recognition factors amongst the state's electorate, with only 45% having any opinion on Angelides and 40% for Westly. Of registered Democrats surveyed, 59% said they didn't know enough about Angelides to have any opinion about him, with 58% saying the same for Westly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://field.com/fieldpollonline/subscribers/RLS2193.pdf |title=RLS2193 for PDF.PDF |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020150806/http://field.com/fieldpollonline/subscribers/RLS2193.pdf |archive-date=2010-10-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that the race for the Democratic nomination was a virtual tie, with Angelides leading Westly by three percentage points (37%-34%), within the 3% margin of error. Unusually, 28% of Democratic voters were undecided, and both candidates tried to earn the undecided vote.\n\nAngelides reported a recent increase in support for his campaign and gained union support as well as support from the \"core\" [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] constituency. The [[California Democratic Party]] endorsed him prior to the primary, despite most polls showing that Westly would fare much better against Schwarzenegger in the general election.<ref>[http://www.californiaprogressreport.com/2006/04/angelides_endor.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509222636/http://www.californiaprogressreport.com/2006/04/angelides_endor.html |date=May 9, 2007 }}</ref> However, many registered Democrats believed that Westly had a greater chance of winning against incumbent governor Schwarzenegger and felt that he had a slightly \"more positive\" image.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/la-me-poll28may28,0,5948271.story?coll=la-story-footer |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20170525040730/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/may/28/local/me-poll28 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2017-05-25 |title=Angelides Pulls Even With Westly \u2013 Los Angeles Times |publisher=Latimes.com |date=2006-05-28 |accessdate=2010-08-14 }} </ref> In the end, Angelides won 47.9% of the vote to Westly's 43.4%. The turnout for the primary, was a record low 33.6%,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://primary2006.ss.ca.gov/Returns/status.htm |title=CA Secretary of State \u2013 Primary Election- County Status |publisher=Primary2006.ss.ca.gov |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828123746/http://primary2006.ss.ca.gov/Returns/status.htm |archive-date=2008-08-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> far below the 38% predicted by the Secretary of State,<ref>[http://www.ss.ca.gov/executive/press_releases/2006/06_078.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060628193518/http://www.ss.ca.gov/executive/press_releases/2006/06_078.pdf |date=June 28, 2006 }}</ref> with the turnout of valid ballots cast on election day at 28%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vote.ss.ca.gov/Returns/gov/00.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060623125421/http://vote.ss.ca.gov/Returns/gov/00.htm |archivedate=2006-06-23 }}</ref>\n\n====Polling====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:lightgrey;\"\n! style=\"width:220px;\"| Source\n! style=\"width:110px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| Westly\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Angelides\n|-\n| [http://www.surveyusa.com/client/PollReportPopup.aspx?g=39f2cf99-2acb-482c-9d16-7f4bd40dd565&q=27450 Survey USA]\n| June 5, 2006\n| <center>36%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''44%'''</center>\n|-\n| [http://www.surveyusa.com/client/PollReportPopup.aspx?g=124546e5-7c2b-4a74-af98-531daf2c8f22&q=27450 Survey USA]\n| June 2, 2006\n| <center>37%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}|<center>'''41%'''</center>\n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20050830025509/http://field.com/fieldpollonline/subscribers/ Field Poll]\n| June 2, 2006\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''35%'''</center>\n| <center>34%</center>\n|-\n| [http://www.latimes.com/la-me-poll28may28,0,5948271.story?coll=la-story-footer ''LA Times'' Poll]\n| May 27, 2006\n| <center>34%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''37%'''</center>\n|-\n| [http://www.surveyusa.com/client/PollReportPopup.aspx?g=a66e0fc1-7956-45be-acf9-bc92c7a1ee82&q=27450 Survey USA]\n| May 25, 2006\n| <center>32%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''44%'''</center>\n|-\n| [http://www.ppic.org/content/pubs/survey/S_506MBS.pdf Public Policy Institute of California]\n| May 25, 2006\n| <center>32%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''35%'''</center>\n|-\n| [http://www.surveyusa.com/client/PollReportPopup.aspx?g=a856efc3-8de7-4791-b180-39f7bb3b58f1&q=27450 Survey USA]\n| May 8, 2006\n| <center>31%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''41%'''</center>\n|-\n| [http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-me-poll29apr29,1,4284067.story?coll=la-headlines-politics&ctrack=1&cset=true ''LA Times'' Poll]\n| April 29, 2006\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''33%'''</center>\n| <center>20%</center>\n|-\n| [http://www.ppic.org/content/pubs/survey/S_406MBS.pdf Public Policy Institute of California]\n| April 27, 2006\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''26%'''</center>\n| <center>20%</center>\n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20050830025509/http://field.com/fieldpollonline/subscribers/ Field Poll]\n| April 17, 2006\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''37%'''</center>\n| <center>26%</center>\n|-\n| [http://www.ppic.org/content/pubs/survey/S_306MBS.pdf Public Policy Institute of California]\n| March 30, 2006\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''23%'''</center>\n| <center>22%</center>\n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20050830025509/http://field.com/fieldpollonline/subscribers/ Field Poll]\n| November 3, 2005\n| <center>26%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''37%'''</center>\n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20050830025509/http://field.com/fieldpollonline/subscribers/ Field Poll]\n| September 7, 2005\n| <center>22%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''32%'''</center>\n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20050830025509/http://field.com/fieldpollonline/subscribers/ Field Poll]\n| June 29, 2005\n| <center>28%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''37%'''</center>\n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20050830025509/http://field.com/fieldpollonline/subscribers/ Field Poll]\n| February 25, 2005\n| <center>11%</center>\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| <center>'''15%'''</center>\n|}\n\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no party no change | title=California gubernatorial Democratic primary, 2006}}\n{{Election box winning candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = [[Phil Angelides]]\n  |votes      = 1,202,851\n  |percentage = 48.00\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = [[Steve Westly]]\n  |votes      = 1,081,940\n  |percentage = 43.18\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = [[Barbara Becnel]]\n  |votes      = 66,550\n  |percentage = 2.66\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = Joe Brouillette\n  |votes      = 42,075\n  |percentage = 1.68\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = Michael Strimling\n  |votes      = 35,121\n  |percentage = 1.40\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = Frank A. Macaluso, Jr.\n  |votes      = 30,867\n  |percentage = 1.23\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = Vibert Greene\n  |votes      = 25,475\n  |percentage = 1.02\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = Jerald Robert Gerst\n  |votes      = 21,039\n  |percentage = 0.84\n}}\n{{Election box total no party no change|\n  |votes      = 2,505,918\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Republican===\n\n====Candidates====\n*Jeffrey Burns \u2013 general contractor\n*Bill Chambers \u2013 railroad switchman\n*Robert C. Newman II \u2013 psychologist and farmer\n*[[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] \u2013 incumbent [[Governor of California]]\n\nRepublican Schwarzenegger faced token opposition and won overwhelmingly in the primary held on June 6, 2006.\n\n====Results====\n\n{{Election box begin no party no change | title=California gubernatorial Republican primary, 2006}}\n{{Election box winning candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]]\n  |votes      = 1,724,281\n  |percentage = 89.99\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = Robert C. Newman II\n  |votes      = 68,660\n  |percentage = 3.58\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = Bill Chambers\n  |votes      = 65,487\n  |percentage = 3.42\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party no change|\n  |candidate  = Jeffrey R. Burns\n  |votes      = 57,652\n  |percentage = 3.01\n}}\n{{Election box total no party no change|\n  |votes      = 1,916,080\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Third parties===\n\n{{Election box begin no change | title=California gubernatorial primary, 2006 (Others)}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Green Party of California\n  |candidate  = [[Peter Camejo]]\n  |votes      = 33,545\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = American Independent Party\n  |candidate  = [[Edward C. Noonan]]\n  |votes      = 29,094\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Libertarian Party of California\n  |candidate  = [[Art Olivier]]\n  |votes      = 16,445\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Peace and Freedom Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Janice Jordan]]\n  |votes      = 3,849\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==General election==\n\n===Candidates===\n*[[Phil Angelides]] ([[California Democratic Party|Democratic]]) \u2013 [[California State Treasurer]], Ex-State Democratic Chair & Developer\n*[[Peter Camejo]] ([[Green Party of California|Green]]) \u2013 2002/2003 Green Party gubernatorial candidate, 2004 independent vice presidential candidate ([[Ralph Nader]]'s running mate)\n*[[Janice Jordan]] ([[Peace and Freedom Party (United States)|Peace and Freedom]]) \u2013 2004 Peace and Freedom Party vice presidential candidate ([[Leonard Peltier]]'s running mate)\n*[[Edward C. Noonan]] ([[American Independent Party|American Independent]]) \u2013 computer shop owner\n*[[Art Olivier]] ([[Libertarian Party of California|Libertarian]]) \u2013 former mayor of [[Bellflower, California|Bellflower]], 2000 Libertarian Party vice presidential candidate ([[Harry Browne]]'s running mate)\n*[[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] ([[California Republican Party|Republican]]) \u2013 incumbent [[Governor of California]], actor, businessman\n\n===Campaign===\nSchwarzenegger's decision to call the [[California special election, 2005|2005 special election]], as well as his propositions dealing with teachers' and [[nurse]]s' [[trade union|unions]] and other political missteps, brought his approval rating down to 39%  April 2006,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/ocregister/news/state/stateelections/article_1100965.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=2006-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930182418/http://www.ocregister.com/ocregister/news/state/stateelections/article_1100965.php |archive-date=2007-09-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> though he ended up solidly defeating his opponents. During his first two years, he came under fire from some conservatives for supporting several taxes on Californians,{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} and from some [[American liberalism|liberals]] for refusing to sign a bill allowing [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|gay marriage]], and his support for several controversial propositions in 2005. Later, Schwarzenegger's popularity with voters rebounded and he won reelection by a wide margin.\n\n===Polling===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:lightgrey;\"\n! style=\"width:260px;\"| Source\n! style=\"width:140px;\"| Date\n! style=\"wi